<HEADLINE> Turkey to Import Russian Oil, Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has decided to import
Russian oil and natural gas, local newspaper Daily News reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made following a meeting of energy officials
from the two countries in Ankara early this week. The two sides
agreed in principle to sign a series of contracts for the
purchase.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement in principle, Turkey is expected to buy
about 10 billion cubic meters of Russian gas.
</P>
<P>
However, the Turkish-Russian deal is attacked by some Turkish
lobbyists, who are allegedly backed by companies of the United
States involved in oil exploitation in the Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
Russian gas is 70 percent more expensive than that provided by
U.S. firms, the lobbyists said, adding that the deal will make
Turkey dependent on Russian energy.
</P>
<P>
But Turkish energy policy-makers said that cooperation with
Russia in this field is favorable to Turkey, describing the
criticism as "baseless." 
</P>
</TEXT>
