<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Air Force Flights Suspended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Air Force
commander-in-chief Pyotr Deinekin on Friday ordered Air Force
flights to suspend for a week, Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Deinekin was quoted as saying that his decision is connected
with "serious air crashes" in December.
</P>
<P>
An air crash happened at the Naryan-Mar airport on December 11
when a military transport plane An-12 rammed a sanitary helicopter
Mi-8, killing eight people with three seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
Not before less than a week on December 6, another air disaster
of a plane An-124 Ruslan occurred in the eastern city of Irkutsk,
which crashed into a block of flats, killing 68 people.
</P>
<P>
Deinekin noted that it is necessary to examine the situation,
carry out studies to inspect planes and then to move further.
</P>
<P>
He said the order is applicable only to flights of the Air
Force and does not cover air defense aviation and marine aviation,
which are necessary for national security and also within the
system of the Russian Defense Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
