<HEADLINE> Britain, France Disagree Over EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, December 12 (Xinhua) -- A dispute between Britain
and France over the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) is dragging
on the feet of other major issues European Union (EU) leaders are
expected to discuss at the two-day summit beginning here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The EU leaders were set to make a deal over the issue before
they could move on to talk about other issues.
</P>
<P>
France has been leading a drive in setting up a Euro council
which will group exclusively EU member countries that are likely
to launch the EMU in January 1999. The council is supposed to
oversee the EU's future economic and monetary policy under a
single currency.
</P>
<P>
It maintains that the council will play a key role in deepening
political ties between EMU members before the EU admits new
members from central and eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
However, Britain hates to be ignored in the EU's discussion of
future monetary and economic policy.
</P>
<P>
"There can't be small clubs that try and take over the running
of the European Union," British Prime Minister Tony Blair was
quoted by media reports as saying.
</P>
<P>
After assuring it will not join the EMU before 2002, Britain is
being backed up on the issue by Sweden, Denmark and Greece, the
three other EU members which expect to stay out of the EMU in
1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
