<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Producer Prices Continue to Decrease in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. producer prices
decreased for the eighth time this year as computers, gasoline and
coffee became cheaper in November, the labor Department reported
here today.
</P>
<P>
Prices paid by wholesalers and others for finished goods fell a
seasonally adjusted 0.2 percent, following three monthly increases
in the Producer Price Index. The index dropped for consecutive
seven months from January through July, which constitutes a
post-World War II record.
</P>
<P>
During the first 11 months of the year, prices have fallen at
an annual rate of 1.2 percent, compared with a 2.8 percent
increase for all of 1996.
</P>
<P>
November's producer price decline was attributed mainly to a
3.1 percent drop in gasoline and broad-based decreases.
</P>
<P>
Food prices inched 0.1 percent lower, helped by drops of 11
percent for vegetables, 8.6 percent for fresh fruit and 5.1
percent for coffee, the biggest decline in more than six years.
</P>
<P>
Cauliflower fell 70 percent; broccoli, 55.1 percent; lettuce,
46 percent; citrus fruit, 29.2 percent, and cantaloupes, 23.2
percent. The cost of beef, poultry and fish also declined, but the
price of fresh eggs shot up 30.6 percent, the highest rate for one
month.
</P>
<P>
Energy prices fell 0.8 percent. A 5.4 percent increase in
heating oil, the most in 19 months, and a 3.8 percent rise in
natural gas partly offset declines for gasoline and electricity.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile food and energy sector, prices sank by
0.1 percent. For the first 11 months of the year, these so-called
core prices, which are considered a better gauge of underlying
goods inflation,_ have risen at an annual rate of just 0.2
percent, down from 0.6 percent for all of 1996.
</P>
<P>
In November, auto prices declined 0.6 percent; light trucks,
0.8 percent, and computers, 2.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The cost of intermediate goods rose 0.2 percent but crude goods
shot up 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, intermediate level prices still were 0.1 percent lower
than a year earlier and crude was off 0.9 percent. Examples of the
three processing stages are bread and clothing for finished, flour
and cloth for intermediate and wheat and cotton for crude.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report today, the Commerce Department said
business inventories rose 0.4 percent in October while sales edged
0.1 percent lower. If continued, that trend could mean a
production slowdown. The report includes retailers, wholesalers
and manufacturers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
