<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Opposition Party Condemns Attack on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's opposition
Democratic Party today condemned the assault of the Zimbabwe
Congress of Trade Unions Secretary General Morgan Tsvangirai by a
group of unknown people and called for a thorough investigation
into the incident.
</P>
<P>
Democratic Party's National Chairman Giles Mutsekwa said in a
statement that his party learnt with utter disgust Thursday's
''barbaric assault'' on Tsvangirai two days after the
organisation led the nationwhide workers' demonstration against
high taxation on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
''The Democratic Party urges that the law takes its course
without fear or favour to serve this country and its law abiding
citizens from anarchy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Mutsekwa said it is in the interest of the government to
exonerate itself by ensuring the culprits are brought to book.
</P>
<P>
Tsvangirai was attacked by a group of an unknown people in his
office and suffered injuries on his face.
</P>
<P>
Assaulted Tsvangirai who is recovering at his harare home
where he met local and foreign media to give an account of the
incident which he said is a ''politically motivated assassination
attempt''.
</P>
<P>
He said his mysterious assailants, six men and two women in
casual clothes, looked like ordinary citizens.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the police in a statement on Friday condemned the
assault on Tsvangirai and said senior police officers had been
deployed to investigate the matter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
