<HEADLINE> COE Media Conference Approves Joint Action Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Press Ministers of the Council
of Europe (COE) today approved a joint action plan in order to
educate the public in new information technology and to improve
services.
</P>
<P>
The ministers made the decision while attending the 5th
European ministerial conference on media policy in the northern
Greek port city of Thessaloniki, the semi-official Athens News
Agency (ANA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
They also stressed the need of narrowing the gap between north
and south Europe in the field of technology and information.
</P>
<P>
General Secretary for Information Yiannis Nikolaou announced
the fundamental principles of the agreement reached at the two-day
conference, which includes the development of training in new
technology, right of access to new services, combating the
portrayal or expression of violence, intolerance, pornography and
organized crime through these services and a study of the impact
of new technologies on human rights in an information society.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the 40 ministers, representatives from the countries
such as Armenia, Canada, Georgia and the United States also
participated in the conference, which opened Thursday with the aim
of studying the development of the information society and its
influence on how society operates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
