<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Stockmarket on Downward Trend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 12 (Xinhua) -- As a cloud of uncertainty
continues to hang over Zimbabwe's economy, the stockmarket, the
second largest one in Africa, ended the week on a downward trend
when the industrial index shed 173 points to close at 7456 today.
</P>
<P>
Even President Robert Mugabe's assurance in
which he said the current slump in the economy was "a temporary
setback", failed to restore investor confidence. This has been
the negative outlook on the market during the past four weeks.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe's state of the nation address on Tuesday contended that
the problems bedevilling the economy were temporary and would
soon subside.
</P>
<P>
The scrapping of tax increases by the government this week,
following outright rejection by workers, members of parliament
and those of the ruling ZANU (PF) also did nothing to arrest the
slide.
</P>
<P>
There has been more selling than buying in the market against
a backdrop of falling share prices since November 14 when the
Zimbabwe Dollar dropped sharply against major currencies.
</P>
<P>
The depreciation of the Zimbabwe Dollar has prompted investors
to shift from the stock exchange to money markets which offer
high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the mining index also dropped on Friday losing 22
points to close at 424. 
</P>
</TEXT>
