<HEADLINE> Situation Remains Tense After Fighting in North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 12 (Xinhua) -- At least 26 people were
today confirmed dead in the heavy fighting between rival
militiamen within the supporters of Somali faction leader Ali
Mahdi Mohamed in North Mogadishu on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Situation in North Mogadishu remains tense despite the
relative calmness on Thursday night and today after the heavy
fighting.
</P>
<P>
Heavily armed militiamen on technical vehicles were seen
consolidating their defensive posotions in the hostile Manobolyo
and Sana junctions where new checkpoints were erected despite
efforts by clan elders, politicians and businessmen to contain
and prevent further bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
The rival militiamen were watching indifferently a peace march
carried out by hundreds of people mainly women, children and the
elderly today.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators were shouting anti-fighting
words and carried placards read "No More Fighting, No More
Bloodshed, No More Civil Strife" and etc.
</P>
<P>
Despite all this, sporadic gunfire could be heard in several
parts in North Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
South Mogadishu's politicians, Muslim scholars and the other
factions have made appeals of ceasefire and called on the North
Mogadishu militia commanders to contain the hostility.
</P>
<P>
This new round of hostility is taking place at a time when all
Somali faction leaders are meeting in Egypt to finalize the
seven-year long civil war and the political deadlock in their
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
