<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Confirms Coming Poll Is His Last </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Incumbent Kenyan President
Daniel arap Moi, 74 and in power since 1978, confirmed in public
today that his running for another five-year term in the December
29 poll will be his last.
</P>
<P>
"This is my last term," Moi told thousands of people crowded
in Nairobi's Nyayo Stadium celebrating Kenya's 34th anniversary
of independence, 17 days before the second multi-party general
elections in the country.
</P>
<P>
Thus cleared any suspicions clouding Kenyans' mind that Moi,
if he is re-elected as widely expected, might intend to seek the
top place again in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Moi called on all political parties to "carry out
their campaigns in a responsible and mature manner" so that
peaceful, free and fair elections can be ensured.
</P>
<P>
"The coming elections will be a test of our maturity and
integrity as a nation" and "crucial to the stability of our
nation," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He called on everyone seeking an elective position in the
forthcoming general elections to "accept the people's verdict
with dignity and in the spirit of unity and patriotism".
</P>
<P>
A total of 15 candidates now are busy campaigning for the
presidency, the most crowded presidential race since Kenya
declared independence in early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
Moi is the sole candidate of the ruling Kenya African National
Union (KANU) party and is effectively taking advantages of the
division of the opposition.
</P>
<P>
His powerful rivals include Mwai Kibaki of Democratic Party of
Kenya, Wamalwa Kijana of FORD-Kenya, Raila Odinga of National
Development Pary of Kenya, Charity Ngilu of Social Democratic
Party and Martin Shikuku of FORD-Asili.
</P>
<P>
A presidential aspirant can be qualified as he (she) gets the
mandatory 1,000 signatures of supporters but to be a legal Kenyan
president needs no less than 25 percent votes in five out of the
country's eight provinces under Kenya's current constitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
