<HEADLINE> Swazi Government Denies Claims to Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The Swazi government has
denied that it has tried to annex the southern part of Mozambique
into its territory, Mozambican Prime Minister Pascoal Mocumbi
said today.
</P>
<P>
According to Mocumbi, the denial was made by the Swazi Foreign
Minister in a document presented to the Mozambican authorities.
</P>
<P>
The document said that "as fraternal and friendly neighbors,
Swaziland and Mozambique have been maintaining good cooperation
relations and their border line will remain unchanged."
</P>
<P>
About two weeks ago, there were reports in two Swazi
newspapers that Swazi Prince Khuzulwandle, Chairman of the Swazi
Committee of Frontier Adjustment, and Senator Bhekimpi said in
parliament Swaziland has rights to annex the southern
Mozambique, including Maputo, into its territory.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican prime minister noted that the claims by the
Swazi parliament members are not helpful for promoting bilateral
relations. He said the Swazi government keeps a distance from
these members of parliament.  
</P>
</TEXT>
