<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Likely to Announce ECB Chief Next March: Observers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) is
likely to announce its nomination of the head of the new European
Central Bank (ECB) in late March of 1998 before it decides on
which countries to join the planned economic and monetary union
(EMU), it was learned here today.
</P>
<P>
Many observers to the ongoing EU summit in Luxembourg made the
forecast after a row over the issue simmered at the start of the
two-day summit on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The issue of nomination was expected to be raised in the
margins of the meeting. Dutch Prime Minister Wim Kok said late on
Thursday that he planned to raise the issue with other EU leaders
attending the summit.
</P>
<P>
But he later told reporters that there would be "no formal
solution" since the issue was not on the agenda, adding that he
did not want the issue to overshadow the EU's talks on
enlargement.
</P>
<P>
France and the Netherlands have been at odds with each other
over the issue since both countries have put forward high-profile
central bankers for the post.
</P>
<P>
Wim Duisenberg, former Dutch central bank chief and current
president of the European Monetary Institute (EMI), has been
widely regarded as the most likely candidate to win the post.
</P>
<P>
In November, France recommended its own candidate for the key
post of EU institutions, its own central bank chief Jean-Claude
Trichet, who said Thursday that it was up to EU leaders to decide
on who should get the job.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that Finnish central bank chief Sirkka
Hamalainen was chosen as a compromise choice for the post.
</P>
</TEXT>
