<HEADLINE> Bulgarian, Greek Leaders Discuss Ties in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Bulgarian Vice
President Todorov Kavaldjiev today met with Greek Parliament
President Apostolos Kaklamanis to discuss ways of expanding
cooperation between the two neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, Kavaldjiev, who is in Athens to attend a
symposium, called on Greek companies to invest in Bulgaria's
privatization program, and pledged that Sofia would promote
pending bilateral issues such as the Burgas-Alexandroupolis
pipeline and new border customs posts.
</P>
<P>
The 300km high-pressure pipeline, which would have a capacity
of 600,000 barrels a day, is expected to bring crude oil from the
Urals from Bulgaria's Black Sea port of Burgas to the northern
Greek port of Alexandroupolis.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Kaklamanis reiterated that Athens backs Sofia
in participating in the construction of Europe.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Bulgarian-Greek relations is developing smoothly
with the two governments sharing the desire of boosting their
political and economic ties. 
</P>
