<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Natives Win on Land Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Canada's native people have a
constitutional right to own their lands and to use them as they
wish, the Supreme Court of Canada has ruled.
</P>
<P>
The decision applies to natives who have not signed away their
lands in treaties and its impacts will be felt in parts of
Atlantic Canada and most of British Columbia province, reports
said today.
</P>
<P>
In a unanimous decision released on Thursday, the Supreme Court
overturned a ruling of B.C. court that dismissed native claims to
ownership of a 58,000-square-kilometres swatch of land in
northwest B.C..
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court concluded that a new trial is necessary and
that the judge should take into account oral histories of the
natives in the new trial.
</P>
<P>
Both the federal and provincial governments have expressed a
willingness to negotiate a settlement.
</P>
<P>
"It's a complete victory for us," said the lawyer representing
the B.C natives in their land-claim fight.
</P>
<P>
"The decision restores a measure of faith in the rule of law,"
said Chief Joe Mathias, a native spokesman in the province.
</P>
<P>
The ruling has increased the power of the natives in
land-claims negotiations, and has direct implications for Canada's
native lands not governed by a treaty, the reports noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
