<HEADLINE> Nigerian Party Threatens to Return Registration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic Party of Nigeria
(DPN) has threatened to return its registration certificate to
the government in a protest over alleged manipulation of the
state legislative election last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Prince Pat Abii, the party's national publicity official was
quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria as saying in Abuja today
that the party is now under pressure from its state chairmen to
boycott the rest of the transition program.
</P>
<P>
The state chairmen were in Abuja to attend an emergency
National Executive Council meeting started on Wednesday to
discuss the party's performance during the election.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the chairmen have even threatened to quit the party
if their demands are not met by the National Executive Council,"
said Pat Abii.
</P>
<P>
The DPN emerged as the second largest party during last
Saturday's election, securing about 151 out of a total of 989
state legislative seats, according to incomplete results
announced by the National Electoral Commission of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The party was complaining of manipulation of the election in
favor of the United Nigeria Congress Party (UNCP), according to
the report. The UNCP was leading all the other four parties with
about 500 seats. 
</P>
