<HEADLINE> UK Publishes Late Payment of Commercial Debts Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 12 (Xinhua) - The British government has
published a Bill to introduce a statutory right for businesses to
claim interest on the late payment of commercial debts.
</P>
<P>
The Bill is a key element in its comprehensive package of
measures developed in partnership with businesses, their
representative organizations and the public sector to improve
Britain's payment problem.
</P>
<P>
Announcing publication of the Late Payment of Commercial Debts
(Interest) Bill, Small Firms Minister Barbara Roche said on
Thursday that the purpose of the Bill is to help businesses tackle
the problem of late payment.
</P>
<P>
"Late payment hits small firms hardest; it stifles growth,
disrupts cash-flow and ultimately hits profits," Roche added.
</P>
<P>
According to the Minister, to give specific help to small
firms, the right to claim interest will be phased in three stages:
</P>
<P>
- The first stage brings the right to small businesses to use
against all large enterprises, including public sector
organizations.
</P>
<P>
- The right will then be extended, after a period, probably two
years, for use by small businesses against all enterprises and the
public sector.
</P>
<P>
- Finally, the right will be extended, again after a probable
period of two years, to cover all enterprises and the public
sector.
</P>
<P>
The Government wants to encourage businesses to agree their own
contractual terms giving a right to interest if bills are paid
late.
</P>
<P>
However, provisions are included in the Bill to prevent
"contracting out" of the legislation by dominant customers setting
excessively low rates of interest or long payment times in their
contracts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
