<HEADLINE> UN Chief Recommends to Extend Mandate of UNMIBH </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 12 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today recommended to extend the mandate of the United
Nations Mission in Bosnia and Herzegovina (UNMIBH) for a further
period of 12 months.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council, Annan said progress had
been made in implementing the General Framework Agreement, much
of it in areas of immediate concern of the UNMIBH operation: the
inauguration of joint Bosnia - Croat police forces in the two
mixed cantons of the Federal; the initiation of a comprehensive
police restructuring program in the Republika Srpska; and the
appointment of a multi-ethnic police leadership in the contested
city of Brcko.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General said police restructuring had to be
accompanied by reform of the judicial system in general. It was
clear that reforming the police, the judicial system and the
prisons must be addressed in an integrated way in order to create
a law and order environment that was fair and non-discriminatory.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief said another area that deserved increased
attention was the loss of revenue to the state through economic
crimes. UNMIBH was ready to begin training entity police forces
in the detection of financial crime, smuggling and corruption,
and to assist in setting up special anti-corruption units.
</P>
<P>
Annan said much had been achieved, but much also remained
to be done. The United Nations was ready to continue to play its
part. In order to carry out the tasks suggested above, he
recommended to extend the mandate of UNMIBH for a further 12 months.
</P>
</TEXT>
