<HEADLINE> German Parliament to Probe Neo-Nazi Trend in Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Germany's parliament today
decided to launch a special probe into a series of neo-Nazi
scandals that have seriously damaged the image of the German armed
forces, the Bundeswehr.
</P>
<P>
The probe, insisted by the German opposition parties, the
Social Democratic Party (SPD) and the Greens, will start next
January with the establishment of a parliamentary investigation
committee.
</P>
<P>
The move was prompted mainly by a major scandal a week ago
after a convicted neo-Nazi, Manfred Roeder, was found to have been
invited to deliver a speech in 1995 to a German military academy
training top officers.
</P>
<P>
On top of that, a number of video tapes have also been made
public over past few months depicting neo-Nazi behavior of German
soldiers ranging from giving the Nazi salute to staging mock
executions and rapes.
</P>
<P>
German Defense Minister Volker Ruehe, whose resignation was
demanded by the SPD last week, has insisted that these cases were
isolated incidents and did not prove that rightist extremism was
rampant within the army.
</P>
<P>
He also accused some leftwing German media today of working
together with Roeder in a deliberate campaign against the army.
</P>
<P>
German opposition parties today stressed that the parliamentary
investigation was meant to ensure the exclusion of neo-Nazis from
the army and would help restore its image. 
</P>
</TEXT>
