<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP to Ease Tanzania's Food Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program
(WFP) has started an emergency operation to deliver relief food
to over 1.4 million people facing food shortage in Tanzania,
after poor performance of both short and long rains last season.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued today by WFP country director
Irene Lacy, the relief food worth 20.7 billion Shillings (about
33 million U.S. Dollars) will be distributed to 48 worst affected
districts.
</P>
<P>
A total of 69,000 tons of maize and 7,000 tons of pulses are
expected to be distributed under a nine-month operation. The
first batch of 300 tons of maize which arrived at the end of last
month in Dodoma is expected to benefit 212,000 people there.
</P>
<P>
The move, according to Lacy, is in response to Tanzanian
President B. Mkapa's latest appeal to the international community
to assist in the procurement of relief food. The president has
declared a state of food emergency in the 1997/98 season.
</P>
<P>
The program, which involves 11 non-governmental organizations
(NGOs), UNICEF and local communities, will give priority to the
most needy, and the rest accordingly, Lacy added.
</P>
<P>
Food distribution will first start in the regions of Dodoma,
Singida, Shinyanga, Mara, Tabora and Arusha, which are in
critical situation. The most seriously affected villages will be
reached this month, said Lacy.
</P>
<P>
However, the WFP country director expressed fears that the
current rains which have cut off a number of villages from major
roads will make their food relief a tough job. But she said all
efforts will be made to ensure the program goes on as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
She pledged that WFP will try to meet members of the United
Nations, NGOs and donor community over the coming weeks to help
the starved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
