<DOCNO> XIE19971213.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Peace Process Remains Stranded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The peace process in Sierra
Leone has become shaky as fresh fightings broke out between the
military junta and traditional Kamajors hunter militias who are
loyal to President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah ousted in the May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued today, the Kamajors said it had to
launch a fresh round of attack against the junta since the
military had failed to implement the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Anyone working in the interest of the junta will be considered
as target, the British Broadcasting Corporation quoted the
release as saying.
</P>
<P>
A Kamajor field commander reportedly accused the junta of
killing a number of people in a town in southeast Sierra Leone in
its attack earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
The entire town was burnt down before the junta forces were
repelled. The junta forces also attacked a town at the border
with Liberia on Thursday, killing 15 people, including women and
children.
</P>
<P>
But in Freetown, junta spokesman Aliu Kamara said today it was
the Kamajors who were attacking and killing people as well as
damaging properties in the southeast of the country.
</P>
<P>
He also blamed the Nigerian troops in the west African peace
keeping force (ECOMOG) for the crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
The junta has been opposed to the dominance of Nigerians in
ECOMOG and the disarmament of the national army since the signing
of a peace accord in Conakry, Guinea last October.
</P>
<P>
A number of talks have since failed to work out modalities to
implement the peace plan, under which the junta agrees to step
down in April next year.
</P>
<P>
While Kamara said the military would assist the disarmament of
other combatants in the country rather than its troops, he
insisted that Nigeria should not be part of ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
The disarmament, originally slated for the period between
December 1 and 31 this year, would begin when Nigerian stands
neutral in the peace process, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"We'll not disarm on schedule if Nigeria keeps bombarding our
innocent civilians and keeps harassing our people with their
jets," Kamara noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
