<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNSCOM Chief Hopes to Settle Access Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 12 (Xinhua)-- U.N. chief arms inspector
Richard Butler said here today that he hoped to settle the access
issue during his four-day visit to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Butler, Chairman of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in
charge of eliminating weapons of mass destruction in Iraq, said
at a press conference that he would cooperate with Iraq to try to
bring the crisis on the arms inspection between the U.N. and Iraq
to an end.
</P>
<P>
"I'm here to try to seek a peaceful solution to what has been
a crisis," said Butler who arrived here today leading a high
level technical team from the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
The Iraq-U.N. crisis, triggered by Iraq's decision on October
29 to expel U.S. weapons inspectors in the UNSCOM, has been eased
after Russia's mediation.
</P>
<P>
Iraq agreed on November 21 to allow U.N. weapon inspectors to
return to Baghdad to resume their work, but has been refusing to
grant access to weapon inspectors to presidential palaces on the
ground that it would infringe Iraq's national security,
sovereignty and dignity.
</P>
<P>
Bulter said he would hold technical talks with the Iraqi side
Sunday, in hopes that the two sides could agree on a further
"special, intensified" program of work in some key weapon areas.
</P>
<P>
The chairman said the issue of access will top his agenda in
discussions with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz Monday,
stressing that "we should be able to go anywhere, anytime."
</P>
<P>
Butler said that he would see if they could find a way to
inspect sensitive sites without infringing Iraq's "legitimate
concerns for national security, sovereignty and dignity."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq after its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait will be lifted only after the UNSCOM submits to the
Security Council a bill of health certifying that Iraq has
destroyed all its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Butler said he would leave Baghdad Tuesday and report to the
Security council the results of his talks with Iraqi government
officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
