<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Working on Big Aid Package to Congo (K): </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said in Kinshasa today the U.S. is working on
a U.S. $35-40 million aid package for Democratic Congo, a report
from the Congolese capital said.
</P>
<P>
The money would come on top of a U.S. $10 million contribution
Albright announced Tuesday that Washington would grant the former
Zaire through a World Bank trust fund, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Albright, speaking after talks with Congolese President
Laurent Kabila, said the U.S. government would prepare the
package jointly with Congress, which has demanded assurances that
Kabila is respecting democracy and human rights before sending
aid.
</P>
<P>
She said the money would be used for infrastructure, health
care, water projects and rebuilding a bridge destroyed by the
forces of ousted President Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. top diplomat, on a seven-nation African tour, arrived
in Kinshasa from Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
While in Kigali Thursday, she pledged U.S. support to Rwanda,
saying the country's future was critical to the region.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference with Rwandan President Pasteur
Bizimungu, Albright Slammed hardline Hutu rebels for failing to
choose peace and national unity.
</P>
<P>
However, she stressed the need for justice in Rwanda and "the
importance of providing security without harm to non-combatants"
-- referring to civilians killed in the army's counter-insurgency
operations.
</P>
<P>
Albright noted that Washington plans to release US $3.9
million in aid for army demobilization, the education of
repatriated refugees and the promotion of democracy and
reconciliation in the central African country.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official will leave Kinshasa for Luanda of Angola
later today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
