<HEADLINE> Roundup: OIC Leaders Agree to Disagree at Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Islamic leaders found that
the approach of "agree to disagree" can best serve their
objectives of closing ranks and enhancing solidarity among
themselves at the just-concluded eighth summit of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC).
</P>
<P>
Almost without difficulty, the leaders adopted reams of
resolutions on a variety of political, economic and cultural
issues facing the Islamic nations, and a "Tehran Declaration"
pledging promotion of Islamic unity, condemning Israel's
occupation of Palestinian and Arab lands, and hoping for the
formation of an Islamic common market.
</P>
<P>
This shows that the approach worked and resulted in
reconciliation which enabled the smooth proceeding of the
three-day summit that, among other things, brought together
Iran, a die-hard against the Middle East peace process, and some
U.S. allies, such as Saudi Arabia and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The summit was attended by delegates from 54 OIC members,
including more than 30 heads of state, vice presidents, crown
princes and prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
It exhibited solidarity by denouncing Israel's continued
occupation of Palestinian and other Arab territories including
Jerusalem, the Syrian Golan Heights and South Lebanon, and
calling for the liberation of all occupied lands and restoration
of Palestinian rights to self-determination and to an
independent and sovereign state with Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
Divisions still exist. Iran, for example, stuck fast to its
opposition to dealing with Israel, which it called
"untrustworthy," and further cited the current deadlock on the
peace process as a proof of the correctness of its stance. Many
Arab countries, on the other hand, pinned their hopes of a
lasting and complete peace on, and committed themselves to, the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
They did agree to disagree. The declaration went through
without even mentioning the peace process. Nor did it urge OIC
members to reconsider, or simply stop dealing with Israel.
</P>
<P>
On other issues, the leaders fully supported a peaceful
solution to the Afghan conflict, and expressed solidarity with
Muslim people of Bosnia-Herzegovina and called for rejection
of the aggression of Armenia against Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
They called for safeguarding the Islamic values and principles,
the revival of Islamic civilization, and its peaceful
coexistence with other civilizations.
</P>
<P>
The leaders emphasized that the goal of establishment of an
Islamic common market constitutes a significant step toward
strengthening Islamic solidarity and enhancing the share of
Islamic world in global trade. However, the embryonic ambitious
and trans-regional project lacks step-by-step planning and will
take a long time to realize.
</P>
<P>
The leaders voiced indignation over the U.S. D'Amato Law,
which aimed to tighten screws of sanctions against Iran and
Libya, and termed it an imposition of U.S. domestic law over
international laws.
</P>
<P>
Their differences over who should host the next summit in
2000 prolonged the concluding session for about five hours. But
they finally decided to award it to Qatar, which alienated
itself from a majority of Arab countries by its insistence in
holding the U.S.-brokered Arab-Israeli economic conference last
month despite strong opposition.
</P>
<P>
Iran emerged victoriously in hosting the December 9-11
summit. The massive turnout in Tehran, in contrast to the scarce
attendance in Doha last month, prompted Iranian leadership to
claim that the country has broken the U.S.-imposed isolation since
its 1979 victory of Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
More striking is the fact that Iran used this opportunity to
improve ties with estranged Arab neighbors and even long-time
foes. It agreed with Iraq on resolving bilateral problems,
consented with Turkey to return their recalled ambassadors to
each other's capitals and undertook with Egypt and Saudi Arabia
to better relations.
</P>
<P>
All these conform to the philosophy of "agree to disagree"
as said by Iran's President Mohammad Khatami. Having achieved
this consensus, what awaits ahead for the OIC is how to
translate their objectives contained in the declaration and
resolutions into well-oriented actions. This time, it is not
without difficulty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
