<HEADLINE> German Parliament Changes Central Bank Law in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Germany's parliament today
approved changes in the country's central bank law in preparation
for the 1999 launch of the single European currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Under the new law, the powerful German central bank, the
Bundesbank, will no longer run a special German national monetary
policy up from July 1998 when the European central bank is due to
be founded to run a common monetary policy for the whole Euro
area.
</P>
<P>
Traditional bank business conducted by the Bundesbank will also
be subject to common guidelines and regulations of the European
central bank.
</P>
<P>
However, during the transition period until 2002, when the Euro
bank notes and coins are due to actually enter into circulation,
the Bundesbank will still retain the right to issue the German
mark bank notes.
</P>
<P>
The Euro is due to be launched in January 1, 1999. Countries to
join the single currency club will be selected in May next year
based on their 1997 economic data, including budget deficit and
overall national debt.
</P>
<P>
The legal amendment made by the German parliament today is
necessary to incorporate the country's national central bank into
the Euro central bank system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
