<HEADLINE> 14 Arrested for Sectarian Clashes in Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Ghanaian police have arrest 14
people since a sectarian clash began in the northwestern town of
Wa three days ago, a police source said today.
</P>
<P>
Late on Wednesday in Wa, 500 km northwest of the capital
Accra, members of the Tijaniya Moslem sect attacked the property
of the Al-Sunni sect after provoking preachings by the latter
group, the source said.
</P>
<P>
By Thursday morning, seven houses, a Mosque, a junior
secondary school, an Arabic school, kiosks and stores belonging
to the Al-Sunni were completely burnt down and their contents
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The car of the regional minister and a police jeep were also
damaged, the source said, quoted by a report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The attack took place despite warning shot by the police while
troops of the army's airborne force have been deployed in the
town, where they have restored order, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The regional security was due to meet today to discuss the
growing religious intolerance in the area.
</P>
<P>
The clash in Wa follows the killing in Tamale, 220 km southeast of
Wa, of an Al-Sunni sect member as he attempted to cut the electricity
of a Tijaniya ceremony, where married women were belly-dancing, an
activity the Al-Sunni frown upon, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
