<HEADLINE> Liberia's Former Warlord Accepts New Appointment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Alhaji Kromah, one of the
former key warlords in the Liberian civil war, said today he has
accepted the offer by President Charles Taylor to lead the newly
constituted National Reconciliation Commission.
</P>
<P>
Kromah, an arch rival of Taylor's in the war and currently in
the Guinean capital of Conakry, said he had a telephone talk with
the president on the peace process in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
As citizens in the country are committed to voluntary programs
during the peace process, he has to accept the offer, the British
Broadcasting Corporation reported.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to Monrovia some time from now to begin to work
out the modalities" for the new job, Kromah said, adding that his
earliest schedule is before Christmas or early January next year.
</P>
<P>
Taylor's government is now upset by last week's murder of an
opposition member of parliament and three members of his family.
</P>
<P>
Four men, including Taylor's aide-de-camp, have been arrested
in connection with the killing of Samuel Dokie.
</P>
<P>
But the murder case seems to have destroyed the confidence of
some Liberians in the country's democratic process.
</P>
<P>
It is yet to be seen what will be brought about when Kromah is
back in Monrovia to chair the new commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
