<HEADLINE> UN Chief Hints at Changes for Oil-for-Food Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General
Kofi Annan today hinted that the United Nations might make some
changes for the oil-for-food deal it signed with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"We are reviewing the scheme and we are going to make it more
effective and efficient," said Annan while addressing officials of
the U.N. Iraq-Kuwait Observation Mission (UNIKOM) at its
headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that he will submit a report to the U.N. Security
Council in January, which he said will review all aspects of the
oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
He will propose to allow Iraq to sell more oil, so that it can
buy more food and medicine to ease the hardship of its people
who are under U.N.-imposed sanctions since 1990 following Iraq's
invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food deal, which was carried out in December 1996,
allows Iraq to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil over six
months.
</P>
<P>
Annan arrived here today from Iranian capital Tehran, where he
attended the eighth summit of the Organization of Islamic
Conference. Upon arrival, he flew by helicopter to UNIKOM
headquarters near the Kuwaiti-Iraqi border.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, he refuted Arab countries' criticism that "the
U.N. is starving" the Iraqis, which he said he has heard during
the Islamic summit.
</P>
<P>
The Arab world "must understand the (U.N. Security) Council has
never intended to punish the Iraqi population. ... If the U.N.
wants to punish the Iraqi population, we would not have even
introduced the oil-for-food scheme."
</P>
<P>
On the mission of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in Iraq,
Annan demanded Iraq cooperate with the chief inspector, Richard
Butler, to allow the arms inspectors to search "wherever they have
reasons to believe the materials are being hidden."
</P>
<P>
Iraq, citing national security and sovereignty, bans the
inspectors from entering the presidential palaces.
</P>
<P>
"I hope they will cooperate with the inspectors so they will
see the light at the end of the Tunnel," said Annan.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. will not lift the sanctions on Iraq until the UNSCOM
has verified that Iraq has complied with the orders issued by the
U.N. in 1991 after the Gulf War to eliminate its weapons of mass
destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
