<HEADLINE> Funeral Held for Jordanian Executed in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 12 (Xinhua) -- A funeral was held today in the
Irbid Governorate for one of the four Jordanians who were
executed Monday by Iraqi authority on charge of smuggling car
spare parts, Jordan's official news agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of King Hussein, local officials attended the
funeral of Walid Mohammed Enseirat in his hometown, some 70
kilometers north of Amman, and conveyed the king's condolences to
Enseirat's family members.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein today condemned the execution of the four
Jordanians by Iraq for the first time since Monday, saying that
the "blood of the Jordanians had never been cheap."
</P>
<P>
Jordan expelled seven Iraqi diplomats Wednesday in retaliation
for the execution and recalled its Charge D'Affaires in Baghdad
Adel Sweidan back home for consultation. It warned that more
actions will be taken.
</P>
<P>
The four Jordanians were seized in January 1996 on charge of
smuggling car spare parts worth 620 Jordanian dinars (about 878
U.S. dollars). They were released on bail in March this year,
then called back for trial in April and sentenced to death in
September.
</P>
<P>
Car parts and many other goods are in short supply in Iraq,
which has been under U.N. sanctions since its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Iraq will execute a fifth Jordanian named
Ammar Ghaleb Shehabeddine soon. There are now over 100
Jordanian prisoners serving their sentences in Iraqi jails.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Iraq used to be firm allies before and during the
Gulf crisis. But after that, the bilateral ties suffered a
setback as Jordan was eager to distance itself away from Iraq to
end international alienation.
</P>
<P>
However, the ties have been picking up in recent years as Iraq
began to provide the kingdom with more oil at discount prices and
kept increasing the volume of imports from Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is a main supplier of humanitarian goods such as food
and medicine for Baghdad under the U.N.-Iraqi oil-for-food
deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
