<HEADLINE> Self-Confidence Important: Indonesian Finance Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Despite the importance of
external support, self-confidence of Southeast Asian countries was
crucial to solving their recent financial problems, Indonesian
Finance Minister Mar'ie Muhammad said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Confidence building becomes the core of the issue, and this is
not merely an economic issue," he said in his keynote address to
the Conference on Tigers in Transition, dealing with the financial
situation mainly in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
"To restore confidence, we should begin at home, although the
support from international communities is highly important," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Clean your desk and put your house in order, otherwise the
guest won't come in," he added.
</P>
<P>
Summing up the lessons drawn from the recent financial crisis
in Southeast Asia, the minister said he thought the crisis was
triggered and worsened by fragility in the financial sector and
heavy foreign borrowing.
</P>
<P>
Short-term borrowing by this region and South Korea was
estimated at 200 billion U.S. dollars and it was unknown how much
more was needed, he said.
</P>
<P>
Another lesson, he said, was that the fundamental microeconomy
at the corporate level became more important as the private sector
was the true market player.
</P>
<P>
He thought the role of the market forces was more dominant
though the role of the government was important.
</P>
<P>
He called for greater transparency of the financial system and
continued comprehensive economic reform.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the external factor, the minister said the global
money market should have a global safety net to minimize the
destabilizing factors which might emerge from huge transactions.
</P>
<P>
The daily volume of global monetary transaction has reached as
high as 2 trillion dollars whose holders and players are pension
funds, insurance companies, mutual funds and commercial banks,
among others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
