<HEADLINE> Turkey Rejects Criticism by OIC Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has reservations on
two resolutions passed at the eighth summit of the Organization
of the Islamic Conference (OIC), a senior official said today.
</P>
<P>
Turkish State Minister Ahat Andican, who just returned from
Tehran following the OIC summit, said that Turkey can not accept
the two resolutions because they failed to reflect the truth,
according to Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The summit, which concluded Thursday, adopted the two
resolutions which criticized Turkey's cross-border incursion in
northern Iraq and its military cooperation with Israel without
giving specific names.
</P>
<P>
Andican stated that Turkey's military operation in northern
Iraq is aimed at wiping out camps of the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK), which has been fighting Ankara for a
Kurdish state since 1984.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue our operations there so long as the PKK
uses the authority vaccum in the region to threaten Turkey's
border security," he said.
</P>
<P>
Turkish leaders have repeatedly announced that Turkey fully
respects the sovereignty and territorial integrity of Iraq within
the framework of international law.
</P>
<P>
On the quickly growing Turco-Israeli military ties, Andican
said that the military cooperation between the two countries is an
issue of bilateral nature.
</P>
<P>
"As we said many times earlier, the Turkish-Israeli
cooperation is by no means directed at a third country," the
minister added.
</P>
<P>
Turkish-Israeli cooperation in military and defense industry
fields has witnessed a quick expansion, provoking harsh criticism
from Muslim countries, especially Arab nations, in the region.
</P>
<P>
Andican also denied press reports that Turkish President
Suleyman Demirel left the summit one day earlier due to his
dissatisfaction with accusations from some Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The president returned to Ankara ahead of schedule as he has
other matters to deal with, he said, describing these press
reports as "groundless." 
</P>
</TEXT>
