<HEADLINE> New Drug Approved for Kidney Transplants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Washington, December 12 (Xinhua) --Zenapax, genetically
engineered new drug for kidney transplant patients, was approved
by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The drug could help prevent the rejection of the
transplanted organ without the side effects of the commonly used
immune system suppressing agents, researchers said.
</P>
<P>
It was developed by Protein Design Labs Inc., a biotechnology
company in Mountain View, Calif., and will be marketed worldwide
by Hoffmann-La Roche Inc..
</P>
<P>
Although designed for kidney transplants, it has been said
to be used with other organs as well, including heart, liver
and lung.
</P>
<P>
Zenapax is one of biotechnology drugs called monoclonal
antibodies which can be extremely selective, binding only with
specific targets while not affecting healthy cells. With it's amino
acid structure being more than 90 percent "humanized", Zenapax
could avoid the allergic response,and human body can accept it as
human proteins. It can stay in the system a very long time, so
it can be more effective.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
