<HEADLINE> Prehistoric Fish Fossils Discovered in Southwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, December 13 (Xinhua) -- Archaeologists have found a
number of fish fossils that date back 70 million years in the
southern part of Sichuan Province in southwest China.
</P>
<P>
The team of scientists uncovered the fossils in a one-square
kilometer area at a tourist resort in Yibin City, and the local
government plans to build a museum to help preserve and display
the finds.
</P>
<P>
Each part of the 15- to 30-cm-long fossilized fish can be
clearly seen, according to an archaeologist, who said that they
are important for the study of biological development, the history
of fish, and geographic changes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
