<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The International Monetary Fund and Russia agreed on a plan
for a quick infusion of 1.7 billion U.S. dollars from the fund and
World Bank. The accord, which would allow for the payment of back
wages and relieve pressure on the ruble, entails a new round of
budget cuts that may be hard to get through Parliament.
</P>
<P>
-- The Internal Revenue Service, quoting from its own internal
audit conducted this fall, admitted that tax-payer rights are
abused by a systemwide "climate" of high pressure that encourages
auditors to go to improper lengths to meet statistical benchmarks.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The United States on Friday banned imports of all cattle and
sheep from Europe until the risk of spreading mad cow disease in
the country is fully examined.
</P>
<P>
-- The United States and about 70 other nations reached
agreement Friday night on a pact to liberalize world markets for
financial services. The accord will open the banking, insurance
and securities markets of a number of fast-growing developing
countries to U.S. firms that have been clamoring for entry.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Times:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright on Friday
called for an end to the ban on political activity in Congo and
said the United States would give aid for the country's
reconstruction. 
</P>
