<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Cracking Down More On Major Corruption Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 13 (Xinhua) -- Beijing will focus its
efforts in anti-corruption work on municipal party and
government departments and law enforcement and the judiciary, Jia
Qinglin, secretary of the Beijing Municipal Party
Committee, said today.
</P>
<P>
Jia made the announcement at the Eighth Beijing Municipal
Congress of the Communist Party of China (CPC), which opened
here yesterday.
</P>
<P>
He said that efforts will be made to uncover corruption cases
in economic administration offices and of officials above the
bureau chief level, with greater focus on the finance, real
estate, land lease, and security market sectors.
</P>
<P>
According to the Beijing discipline inspection and supervision
departments, the city in the past five years has made
investigations into nearly 6,000 cases of violations of Party
disciplines and laws.
</P>
<P>
By October, 5,000 cases were settled and 15 million yuan (1.8
million US) worth of potential economic loss halted.
</P>
<P>
Jia called for Party officials in the city to discipline
themselves and to be honest in performing their duties, adding
they should learn a lesson from Chen Xitong and Wang Baosen and be
on guard against any corrupt acts.
</P>
<P>
Chen Xitong was relieved of his position of secretary of the
Beijing Municipal Party Committee when he was discovered to have
been involved in criminal activities in 1995. Wang Baosen, who was
vice-mayor, was also found to have been involved in criminal
activities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
