<DOCNO> XIE19971213.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladeshi Govt, Opposition on Collision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 13 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government
appears to be on a collision course with the opposition over the
recently signed Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Both are busy preparing political offensives against each other
centering on the peace treaty signed between the government and
the CHT Tribal Organization on December 2.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Awami (People's) League (AL) has decided to call a
parliamentary session to discuss the agreement, while the
opposition parties with the Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) as
the leader have chosen not to go for any kind of legal battle over
the agreement, but rather to face the situation politically.
</P>
<P>
The AL is also planning to hold a series of meetings to garner
the public's support for the peace deal.
</P>
<P>
The BNP-led seven opposition political parties Friday began to
seek opinions from different professional groups in connection
with their campaign against the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Begum Khaleda Zia, BNP Chairperson and leader of the opposition
in parliament, said Friday that the opposition "would wage a
movement to unseat the government if it did not rescind the
agreement" on the CHT issue.
</P>
<P>
Khaleda Zia, the former prime minister, also said that her
party would intensify its campaign against the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The BNP and its supporters have staged hartals almost every
day, particularly in the CHT, since the signing of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
BNP Legal experts said the agreement had not yet come into
force as relevant laws required for its implementation were not
yet enacted.
</P>
<P>
The AL, at its working committee meeting on Thursday, decided
to launch an all-out campaign to win support for the accord.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, some political parties have urged the
government to take appropriate steps to establish a national
consensus over the issue.
</P>
<P>
"Crisis will come and crisis will go," Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina, who is AL chairperson, said Friday. "When we are in
politics and in power, we will have to solve the crisis and we
will do it."
</P>
<P>
"Necessary steps to solve the crisis will be taken," she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
