<DOCNO> XIE19971213.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: American Scholar Devoted to HK Studies (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 13 (Xinhua) -- A black and white portrait
of Confucius on the wall, a big kite featuring owl -- the Western
symbol of wisdom -- beside the computer, and on top of the shelves
 the British Union Jack and Hong Kong's bauhinia flag.
</P>
<P>
That is the very first glimpse of Dr. Michael DeGolyer's small
and compact office in the new campus of Hong Kong Baptist
University.
</P>
<P>
The office is somewhat an epitome of Hong Kong, where East
meets West in a free and frequent way, the associate professor of
government and international studies joked.
</P>
<P>
He came to Hong Kong in mid-1988 with his wife and son, and
first taught at the History Department. There was not a Government
 and International Studies Department at the then much smaller
Baptist College.
</P>
<P>
"I just wanted to study overseas, live overseas and work
overseas for a while, because I study history, political economy
and comparative economy," DeGolyer recalled why he had quit his
teaching job at an American university and settled in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
His keen academic interest in Hong Kong led to years' devotion
to a research project on the handover, involving social scientists
 at various local universities as well as overseas.
</P>
<P>
Since February 1989, DeGolyer has been on the Hong Kong
Transition Project, which aims to study the transition of Hong
Kong from British colonial rule back to China, and its
far-reaching impact on Hong Kong, China and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
"Prior to the handover, we did 18 telephone surveys, about
twice a year, interviewing 600 to 1,200 residents each time," said
 DeGolyer, director of the project. Following each survey was
heavy workload of analyzing and writing.
</P>
<P>
The last survey report before July 1 showed that there remained
 a fairly high degree of optimism among Hong Kong people, with
about 60 percent of the respondents said they were "very
optimistic" or "optimistic".
</P>
<P>
Concerning the expectations in the next decade from now, 44
percent expected Hong Kong to be "better" and 11 percent "about
the same".
</P>
<P>
Now with Hong Kong being a Special Administrative Region (SAR)
of China, the project is starting a new series of surveys which
will go forward to the year 2007, the tenth anniversary of the
handover.
</P>
<P>
"We are revising some of the questions," Dr. DeGolyer. For
example, Hong Kong's integration with the inland areas of China is
 more closely watched. The first post-handover survey report is
due to release next January.
</P>
<P>
"What we are trying to do is to understand this process better
as you know 'one country, two systems' is a kind of new concept, "
 he explained. "The group is a multi-disciplinary one, looking at
various aspects of Hong Kong's development."
</P>
<P>
The research work made DeGolyer a target of the media -- he has
 an average of five interviews and briefings every week.
</P>
<P>
He gets up between four and five in the morning to study until
seven, then listens to radio, watches TV news and, reads papers
and magazines if there isn't an early class.
</P>
<P>
"So I can keep up with what's going on in Hong Kong and Asia,"
DeGolyer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971213.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: American Scholar Devoted to HK Studies (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the recent regional financial turmoil, Hong Kong has done
much better than other Asian economies, DeGolyer said.
</P>
<P>
"There are some areas we need to look at, for example, our
distorted property market, but on the other side if you look at
competitiveness, Hong Kong came out second or third on most of the
 lists," he added.
</P>
<P>
He was excited about the prospects of Hong Kong: "China is set
to grow and Hong Kong has a position of growth leadership in
China's economic development."
</P>
<P>
But, speaking of the education field, the scholar turned
critical.
</P>
<P>
"In the U.S. people graduate from high school and go on to
university study. In Hong Kong, it's only 18 percent, which means
we are only educating less than one person out of five."
</P>
<P>
Even worse, "in a wealthy society like Hong Kong, 40 or 50
percent of our primary students go to school only half-day (for
lack of school buildings)."
</P>
<P>
It is something Hong Kong really needs to improve, DeGolyer
said.
</P>
<P>
His family has fostered a deep feeling toward the city. "We
prefer to live in Hong Kong than anywhere else. We like Hong Kong
very much."  
</P>
</TEXT>
