<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Demands Efforts by Turkey to Gain Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, December 13 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) leaders
said Saturday Turkey was eligible for EU membership but had to
meet certain criteria before being allowed into formal entry talks.
</P>
<P>
It was politically difficult, they agreed at a summit beginning
Friday, to exclude Turkey from a "European family" though the
country had "serious problems" for joining the enlargement process.
</P>
<P>
Frustrated with the regional bloc's reluctance to consider
giving it a seat around the table for entry talks, Ankara snubbed
an invitation to dine with EU leaders on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Turkey insists the EU make clear that it has candidate status.
</P>
<P>
The EU has demanded Ankara to live up to Europe's democratic
values, improve human rights record and relations with neighboring
Greece, and allow EU entry talks with Cyprus to go ahead.
</P>
<P>
Here at two-day summit, EU leaders decided to launch a European
Conference to bring EU members and EU applicant countries together.
</P>
<P>
They decided to invite the 10 central and eastern European
candidates, Cyprus and Turkey first to attend the conference,
which will take place annually for discussions on the enlargement.
</P>
<P>
EU Commissioner Hans van den Broek said Friday the conference
would lack substance if Turkey was not attending.
</P>
<P>
But the leaders also maintained that the invitees must meet
criteria laid out by the EU in the first place, such as respect of
international law and commitment to peace and dispute settlement
by peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the entry talks would start early next year
with Poland, the Czech Republic, Hungary, Estonia, Slovenia and
Cyprus, applicants the EU considers to be advanced in their
required economic and political reforms.
</P>
<P>
The other five candidates, Romania, Slovakia, Lithuania,
Bulgaria and Latvia, will move towards EU membership on a slower
track, with the promise of a place in the world's biggest single
market once they have met its criteria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
