<HEADLINE> Unexploded Japanese Bomb Discovered in Eastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese fishermen recently
discovered an unexploded aerial bomb in the water off Lianyungang
in east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Chinese military experts say the bomb was probably dropped by a
Japanese bomber during the Anti-Japanese War from 1937 to 1945.
</P>
<P>
Luo Gongping, one of the fishermen, discovered the bomb on
November 21 along with fellow fishermen in the sea two miles off
Lianyungang's Kaishan Island.
</P>
<P>
Local military experts say the 400-kilogram bomb is 1.23
meters long with a diameter of 0.38 meters. It is too rusty to
read any identifying marks, they say, but guess from its shape
that it might have come from a Japanese bomber during the
bombardment of the city in 1938.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
