<HEADLINE> Australian Republicans Continue Strong Showing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 13 (Xinhua) -- Australian republican
candidates for next year's constitutional convention are
continuing to outpoll rival monarchists in at least four states in
a ballot with just over 50 percent of the votes counted
nationally.
</P>
<P>
However, the Australians for a Constitutional Monarchy (ACM)
party is outperforming the Australian Republican Movement (ARM) in
Queensland.
</P>
<P>
The vote is too close to call in Tasmania, the Northern
Territory and South Australia.
</P>
<P>
The voluntary poll is to decide the 76 delegates who will join
76 appointed delegates at the February constitutional conference
to discuss whether Australia should be a republic or a
constitutional monarchy.
</P>
<P>
Australian Electoral Commission (AEC) figures showed that the
ARM is outpolling its rivals by two to one in the most populous
state of New South Wales with about 50 percent of the vote
counted.
</P>
<P>
The republicans are also storming past the monarchists in
Victoria with about 38 percent of the votes counted.
</P>
<P>
Results from the other two states, Western Australia and the
Australian Capital Territory, also put the republican delegates in
a winning position with most of the votes counted.
</P>
<P>
But AEC electoral officer Brien (Brien) Hallet has called for
caution in reading the results, saying the vote was too early to
call and difficult to read.  
</P>
</TEXT>
