<HEADLINE> Zambian President Slashes High Houses Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 13 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba slashed prices of council houses when he discovered
irregularities by the Lusaka City Council Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba, who is on a surprise tour of Chunga compound, ordered
the council to review the prices of houses in the area and told
resident who have paid more than 400,000 Kawacha (about 300 U.S.
dollars) for a one bed-roomed house not to make any more payment
because that figure is beyond what he thought was reasonable,
reported the Zambia Daily Mail.
</P>
<P>
He described the high prices of houses as not only
exploitative but an affront to government policy of citizens'
empowerment.
</P>
<P>
He wondered how the council valued the houses and said he
could even have given them for free if he had known earlier.
</P>
<P>
"This is theft, you cannot sell these houses, one bed-roomed
structures which are falling off at 1.6 million kwacha (about
1,200 dollars). These people will have to do renovations when
they buy these things. So how much do you want them to pay? You
must be serious," the president told a official from Chunga
office.
</P>
<P>
He said the government policy of house ownership is not meant
to raise revenue for councils but to give people a chance to own
their houses.
</P>
<P>
Zambia started to sell government and council houses to their
sitting tenants last year as a new housing policy to back house
ownership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
