<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Countries Urged to Increase Regional Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad today proposed that ASEAN countries should
increase trade among them to help cushion the effects of the
currency devaluation and shorten the region's economic recovery
period.
</P>
<P>
"I feel quite sure that the devaluation of our currencies can
facilitate trade between us," he told the opening of a four-day
"Private Sector Salute to ASEAN" meeting which is to mark the 30th
anniversary of ASEAN and in conjunction with the second ASEAN
Informal Summit in Kuala Lumpur on December 14-16.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said there were many things which ASEAN countries
could not buy from each other before and which should be
competitive now "if we keep our new exchange rate and the price of
goods according to the domestic market."
</P>
<P>
By taking advantage of the simultaneous devaluation of the
region's currencies, he said, members of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) could actually increase their
trade with each other without keeping out other countries.
</P>
<P>
"That way we will help each other's economy to recover and
hopefully to grow," he said. "When we are rich again and able to
afford the imported goods and luxuries from outside ASEAN, we
should do so. Indeed, we will be helping to restore world trade by
working hard to recover quickly."
</P>
<P>
As all the ASEAN currencies had been devalued to almost the
same extent, the exchange rates between them had not changed much,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"We can therefore continue our trade with each other almost as
we did before. Indeed we can extend our trade greatly if our
regional sources retain this competitiveness," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that in this regard, the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA)
could be re-examined to expedite and expand it.
</P>
<P>
"If we want to make AFTA worthwhile, we have to guard against
the inflationary effect of devaluation. It is not impossible to do
this. It requires a great deal of discipline among our people,"
Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that he was not advocating ASEAN economic
regionalism, saying the fact was that "We have less money now and
we should buy from the cheapest source."
</P>
<P>
He said there should be no restriction on others entering the
ASEAN markets with their products. "But if their prices are higher
we should not buy from them."
</P>
<P>
As a last resort, ASEAN countries could barter to increase
their trade "since we don't know when the pressure on our
currencies will be lifted," Mahathir said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971213.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
