<HEADLINE> Nanjing Marks Massacre Anniversary (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 13 (Xinhua) -- Exactly Sixty years ago, five
months after Japan launched a full invasion, the eastern Chinese
city of Nanjing, then the capital of China, was captured by the
Japanese intruding troops.
</P>
<P>
The following six weeks and more became a bloody nightmare for
the over 500,000 peaceful residents and nearly 100,000 disarmed
Chinese soldiers in Nanjing, as the Japanese occupants indulged
themselves in an orgy of slaughter, arson, rape and loot.
</P>
<P>
Various records, including those made by the Japanese, showed
that at least 300,000 Chinese were butchered and more than 20,000
women raped. One third of the city's streets and buildings were
burnt to the ground, causing a property loss of 230 billion yuan
(about 28.75 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Also known as "the Rape of Nanking", the Nanjing Massacre was
later described as "a dark page in modern human civilization" by
historians worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Though a long time has passed and Nanjing is now a beautiful
and vibrant provincial capital with a population of over five
million, what happened here six decades ago has become a perpetual
wound to the city and its people that aches most this very day.
</P>
<P>
At ten o'clock this morning, all sirens in Nanjing sounded a
three-minute alarm. The city government designed this ritual last
year for mourning the massacre victims and reminding the local
residents of the past tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, over 3,000 people gathered in a large square outside
the suburban Jiangdongmen Museum, built for the memory of the
massacre victims, for a special memorial service.
</P>
<P>
By the side of a large wreath, which is made of fresh flowers
and two meters in diameter, Sun Han, chairman of the Jiangsu
Provincial Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference, blasted a few Japanese right wingers and
their political representatives for repeatedly trying to deny the
existence of Nanjing Massacre.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971213.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nanjing Marks Massacre Anniversary (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Starting November 24, the Nanjing City Notary Association began
to certify material evidence and testimony provided by these old
people. Li Xiuying was among the first group of 150 survivors to
testify in front of a video camera.
</P>
<P>
Nanjing-based publishing houses also published a series of
books cataloguing Japanese atrocities, which include an
eight-volume diary of German businessman John Rabe, who helped
protect some 250,000 Chinese refugees during the massacre, and a
picture album that collects 800 pictures about the massacre.
</P>
<P>
The curator Zhu said that this year his museum organized a
touring exhibition on the Nanjing Massacre in the country's seven
major cities including Beijing, Shanghai and Wuhan. The exhibition
received a total of one million visitors.
</P>
<P>
"In Hefei alone, 250,000 people came to the exhibition. That's
one third of the city's population," he said. Hefei is the capital
city of east China's Anhui Province.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhu, memorial services for the victims of Nanjing
Massacre were held today not only in Nanjing and China, but also
in many other parts of the world, such as the United States,
Japan, Canada, Australia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
In Japan, he said, memorial concerts were held simultaneously
in Tokyo and Osaka this afternoon, and 11 massacre survivors and
historians from Nanjing were invited.
</P>
<P>
"From this we can see that the world has not forgot this
tragical episode of human history, and that peace and development
have become the common theme for the mankind," he said. "We shall
draw lesson from history and work together for the eternal peace
of the world." 
</P>
</TEXT>
