<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nanjing Marks Massacre Anniversary (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The reason we're holding this service here today is to teach
our people, especially our younger generation, that they shall
never forget history and the national shame if they want to
prevent such kinds of historical tragedy from happening again," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Li Xiuying, one of the survivors of Nanjing Massacre, lit a
"lamp of eternal brightness", traditional tribute to the dead in
China.
</P>
<P>
Li, 78, was stabbed 37 times by Japanese soldiers on December
19, 1937 when she resisted their rape attempts.
</P>
<P>
"I and the scars on my body are the living evidence of the
Nanjing Massacre," said the old lady emotionally.
</P>
<P>
The people released 3,000 pigeons at the end of the service to
express their resentment against war and wishes for world peace.
</P>
<P>
Similar services were held in other 13 places across the city,
all major sites of slaughter 60 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Chengshan, curator of the Jiangdongmen Museum, noted that
it is not on December 13 only that the people in Nanjing and other
parts of the country remember the massacre and its victims.
</P>
<P>
From early July to late September this year, he said, over
11,800 students from 121 universities and middle schools in
Nanjing searched almost every corner of the city for any living
victims, survivors and witnesses of the massacre.
</P>
<P>
Their efforts were joined by a group of Japanese students from
14 schools in Osaka, Tokyo and other cities in mid August.
</P>
<P>
After visiting nearly 30,000 households, the Chinese and
Japanese youngsters found a total of 2,630 old people who were in
Nanjing in that horrible winter of 1937-38.
</P>
</TEXT>
