said Iran, who had taken the rockiest path to qualify, are the
most possible Asian team to make the second round next year in
France.
</P>
<P>
The Arab squad, staging an astonishing comeback to edge out
Australia on away-goal rule in the Asia-Oceania play-off and grab
the last ticket for France, had a wealth of talented players.
</P>
<P>
"The Iranian team have six players who are exceptionally
gifted," Velappan said.
</P>
<P>
Iran's playmaker Karim Bagheri, striker Khodadad Azizi and Ali
Daei, all of whom play professional football in the Bundesliga,
were playing a huge part in Iran's World Cup campaign, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian, saying 1997 was a good year for Asian football
since four teams have qualified for the World Cup finals, reveal
he was particularly glad about the Iranian victory.
</P>
<P>
"The Iranian win is psychologically very important for Asian
football, and I will have a strong case presented to FIFA to ask
for six Asian seats in the 2002 World Cup since Japan and South
Korea are automatically qualified."
</P>
<P>
And the other Asian team Velappan would bet on at next year's
World Cup is South Korea.
</P>
<P>
"I have pleasant feelings about all our four teams next year in
France," he said, "Iran and South Korea are most favoured to
qualify for the next round and surprises may come from Japan and
Saudi Arabia."  
