<HEADLINE> Pakistan Urges Technological Cooperation Among Muslim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 13 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Minister for
Science and Technology Abida Hussain today called for greater
cooperation among Muslim countries in the field of Science and
Technology.
</P>
<P>
Opening an international seminar on "Science and Technology
Strategies for National development," Abida said the Pakistani
government was keen to promote science and technology, vital for
the country's socio-economic development.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, organized jointly by the Committee on Scientific
and Technical Cooperation (COMSTECH) and the Pakistan Academy of
Sciences, is being attended by scientists, researchers and policy
makers from 12 countries, mostly Muslim nations.
</P>
<P>
She hoped that discussions would help the Islamic world in
building a sound scientific infrastructure leading to economic
prosperity of Muslim Ummah (world).
</P>
<P>
The seminar is being held prior to the eighth COMSTECH General
Assembly Meeting here next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
She said ministers of science and technology from 55 member
states of the Organization of the Islamic Conference will attend
the COMSTECH General Assembly Meeting and review the present state
of science and technology in the Muslim countries.
</P>
<P>
Abida expressed the hope that the recommendations of the
seminar and the COMSTECH General Assembly meeting would help
policy makers and scientists in formulating policies for
development of science and technology and for socio-economic
development in the Muslim world.
</P>
<P>
She also praised the Islamic Development Bank (IDB) for its
economic support to COMSTECH in implementing its projects and
policies.  
</P>
