<HEADLINE> Large Charity Event Held in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 13 (Xinhua) -- A large charity event was held
in the Chinese capital today, with the money of about 800,000 yuan
raised on the event donated to the China Disabled Persons'
Federation.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that such an event has been held in
China, which featured a bazaar selling art works and crafts made
by disabled people and a lucky draw with prizes donated by
companies, according to Ni Lin, an official with the federation.
</P>
<P>
He added that it was also the largest donation the federation
had obtained from the business circle, and "all the money raised
on the event is to be used to finance the federation's
poverty-relief programs for the disabled."
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 people from locally based companies, embassies,
and disabled people from Beijing and Tianjin took part in today's
event at Beijing Riviera Country Club, and some disabled artists
displayed their skills in painting, Chinese calligraphy, carving,
and handicrafts making on the event.
</P>
<P>
The event was organized by Beijing Hong Kong Garden Villa House
Property Development Co. Ltd. upon the initiative of Mr. and Mrs.
Heine of Tyssen, a German couple.
</P>
<P>
China has more than 60 million disable people, which involve
one fifth of its households. And the handicapped accounted for
over one third of the country's 58 million rural impoverished
population.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1996-2000 work plan of the China Disabled
Persons' Federation, it will, during the period, help ensure that
almost all poor disabled people get enough to eat and wear,
rehabilitate three million disabled people, and improve the
employment rate for the disabled from the present 70 percent to 80
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
