<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea to Implement Bailout Agreement with IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 13 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's senior political
leaders made a joint statement Saturday, promising to implement a
bailout agreement signed with the International Monetary Fund on
December 3 to regain international confidence in the nation's
economy.
</P>
<P>
The statement was issued after a 70-minute meeting at
Chongwadae by President Kim Young-sam, Lee Hoi-chang, the
presidential candidate of the Grand National Party, Kim Dae-jung,
presidential runner of the National Congress for New Politics, and
Rhee In-je, presidential candidate of the New Party by the People.
</P>
<P>
The four leaders discussed at the meeting how to restore
international confidence in South Korea's economy in a hope of
finding a quicker resolution to the financial panic gripping the
country since November.
</P>
<P>
"We will exert utmost efforts to regain international
confidence and expeditiously stabilize the nation's financial
market by implementing the agreement singed between the government
and the IMF," they said.
</P>
<P>
They also urged the public to share the burden of dealing with
the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We appeal to the entire people to be united as one and make
even more strenuous efforts to overcome the economic crisis by
enduring all the pains," the four political leaders said in the
statement.
</P>
<P>
The country's financial crisis has been deepening as businesses
grasping for funds are becoming increasingly restless over the
skyrocketing value of the U.S. dollar against the nation's won.
</P>
<P>
The rapid depreciation of the won has sent exports and imports
into near paralysis while some industrial sectors are cutting
production under snowballing exchange losses.
</P>
<P>
The won's depreciation is also afflicting huge exchange losses
on the airline, oil refinery and shipping sectors, which heavily
depend on oil imports.
</P>
<P>
The financially-troubled country, which has ordered 14 merchant
banks' suspension of business operation this month, is estimated
to need about 20 billion U.S. dollars to boost foreign currency
flows.
</P>
<P>
The nation's financial crisis was caused by failures of some
corporates and bad loans of financial institutions, estimated at
more than 30 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
With a debt of 110 billion U.S. dollars, South Korea, which is
the world's 11th largest economy, accepted the 57-billion-dollar
IMF loans with strict conditions on December 3 after hard
negotiations with the monetary organization.
</P>
<P>
Those conditions include budget cuts, higher interest rare,
bigger taxes, and a wide opening of its financial market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
