<HEADLINE> Ankara Denounces EU Presidency's Remarks Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 13 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish Foreign Ministry
spokesman has said that the remarks of the European Union (EU)
Presidency describing Turkey as a country practicing torture are
"unacceptable, baseless, humiliating and regretful."
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News today quoted Spokesman Necati Utkan
as saying that "Turkey had listened to righteous criticisms over
its human rights conditions, took them into consideration and
displayed serious and good-willed efforts to overcome these
deficiencies," which have also been explained to the parties
concerned in the EU.
</P>
<P>
He also said "Turkey is also a country proud of the fact that
it has steered clear of xenophobia and intolerance."
</P>
<P>
In his interview with the "Luxemburger Wort" newspaper
Thursday in advance of a two-day summit of EU leaders in
Luxembourg, Prime Minister Jean-Claude Juncker said "I do not
believe the human rights problems can be solved in three to five
years (in Turkey)."
</P>
<P>
Juncker is now holding the EU's rotating presidency and is
hosting the Luxembourg EU Summit.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that "it can not be that the representatives of a
country in which torture is still going on can sit at the table
of the European Union."
</P>
<P>
Juncker said that Turkey can begin talks with the EU now but
the talks will never conclude until Turkey's human rights
problem is fully resolved, adding that "in my opinion Turkey
really has a place in the EU but this process will take decades."
</P>
<P>
Turkey, an associate EU member since 1963, was excluded Friday
from the EU enlargement process although it submitted its
application for EU membership a decade ago. Turkey is accused of
failing to satisfy the EU's political criteria, such as improved
human rights record and respect of democracy.
</P>
<P>
Turkish leaders complain they are thus treated as a
third-ranked nation by the EU. Turkey has turned down the
invitation for the Turkish prime minister to dine with the EU
leaders Saturday after the summit's conclusion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
