<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Warns S. Leone Junta on Attacking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 13 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping force
(ECOMOG) Friday warned the illegal regime in Sierra Leone to stop
its attacks on civilians, or face consequences of its
actions.
</P>
<P>
An ECOMOG statement accused the Revolutionary United Front (RUF)
and its allies of intensifying their raids since December 9 and 10 on
the eastern and southern parts of the country, the Daily Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The statement, signed by Major S.O. Adewusi on behalf of ECOMOG
force Commander Major-General Victor Malu, named Joru and Gorahun in
the east and Sonoshun, Fairo and Dia in the south as areas mostly
affected.
</P>
<P>
The former rebel group RUF has allied to the national army since
the May 25 this year coup overthrew the legitimate government of
President Ahemd Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
"These attacks were backed by helicopter gunship, artillery, mortar
rocket propeller grenade and other small arms. These attacks afforded
the rebel troops the opportunity to loot, rape and traumatize innocent
citizens," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Those mostly affected were children, women and the old, some
of whom managed to escape and are being treated by ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
Also affected in the unprovoked attack were the civil defense corps
known as Kamajors, a group of traditional hunters loyal to President
Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
The statement charged the military junta to intend to push the
Kamajors back and enter the ECOMOG location to create avenue for
more damages on the civilians.
</P>
<P>
The Kamajors and the junta forces have reportedly been in tense
fighting the southeastern Sierra Leone since Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Considering these attacks as a serious violation of the Conakry
peace accord on Sierra Leone, ECOMOG high command reminded the junta
of the grave consequences of its actions.
</P>
<P>
"This high command is therefore constrained to reiterate its
preparedness and commitment to enforce the ceasefire. The junta is
therefore warned that any further violation will inevitably draw
appropriate action from the ecomog high command," said the statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
