<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Condemns Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 13 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government will
not allow people to use demonstrations as instruments for
robbery, thieving or as spring-boards for acts of disorder and
general rampaging, said Zimbabwean president Robert Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
Addressing officers from the presidential office and cabinet
members Friday, President Robert Mugabe said that the predictable
linkage between demonstrations and violence should be prevented
from going on.
</P>
<P>
"If people have a grievance and they want to express it
through a demonstration, why should they be stopped if they do so
in an orderly way? To me that's perfectly in order." he said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting publicly for the first time since Tuesday's
nationwide mass protest against levies, Mugabe said the problem
arose when demonstrations were used to commit acts of crime.
</P>
<P>
He said the government condemned violence in all its forms and
it should be avoided by all means.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe also condemned the assault on Secretary-General of the
Zimbabwean Congress of Trade Unions (ZCTU) Morgan Tsvangirai, who
was attacked by unknown assailants in his office Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
But he said trade unions should learn the discipline of
self-control and break the now assumed linkage between violence
and demonstrations, especially in Harare.
</P>
<P>
He said if the union was being used by white farmers to fight
the policy of giving land to the people the government will
regard them as enemies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
