<HEADLINE> Albright to Meet Egyptian FM on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright will have brief talks with Egyptian Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa Tuesday on the crumbling Palestinian-Israeli
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will take place when Albright, finishing her
African tour, makes a stopover at Cairo Airport on way to Europe
for a North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) summit on December
16-17.
</P>
<P>
The Albright-Moussa talks will focus on the Israeli Likud
government's much-delayed second-phase troop redeployment in the
West Bank, the Middle East News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
She has held two rounds of separate talks with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat within a month and plans a third round
next week, with Netanyahu in Paris and with Arafat in London.
</P>
<P>
Albright said earlier that she expects Netanyahu and Arafat to
"make firm decisions" before their meetings again, meaning that
Israel must make a concrete decision on the second pullback while
the PNA has to make a harsher crackdown on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Washington is growing impatient with Israel's handling of the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process, especially the delays in the
second redeployment in the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
