<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 13 (Xinhua) -- Former Zambian President
Kenneth Kaunda will attend the inter-party talks scheduled for
next month if the government guarantees his safe return from a
protracted overseas trip, said the United National Independence
Party (UNIP) led by Kaunda.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia today quoted UNIP Secretary of Information and
Publicity Bweendo Mulengela as saying there is no doubt that
Kaunda, who went abroad on the eve of the October 28 coup
attempt, will attend the crucial talks, "but the ball is in the
government's court. They should guarantee that he returns home
safely".
</P>
<P>
Mulengela, who attended the preliminary meeting held earlier
this week to map out an agenda for the inter-party dialogue, said
the concern of most opposition parties is that the preliminary
talks might have been done as a display for other influences and
warned that the talks will fail if they are not genuine.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Zambia Democratic Congress (ZDC) has said that
it will go ahead with the inter-party talks whether its president
Dean Mung'omba currently in detention for his alleged involvement
in the foiled coup is released or not.
</P>
<P>
ZDC Vice-President Wynter Kabimba said: "We are still a party
even with detention of our president. We want him out of there
but ZDC will still attend the talks if things go beyond our
control to have him around."
</P>
<P>
The preliminary meeting has been hailed as successful by
opposition parties and non-government organizations.
</P>
<P>
National Party Secretary Standwell Mapala said that he hoped
that the same spirit that prevailed during the preliminary
meeting would also prevail when the inter-party dialog to be
attended by party presidents is held. 
