<HEADLINE> Floods Ravaging Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 13 (Xinhua) -- Floods caused by
continuing heavy rains in different parts of Tanzania have made
hundreds of people homeless and created transport problems,
especially along the central railway line.
</P>
<P>
The floods have also caused a reduced supply of cattle from
upcountry to Dar es Salaam, raising prices of meat.
</P>
<P>
The shortage of supply was caused by the poor state of roads
and the central railway line caused by continuous rains which
have been pounding for the last two weeks, The Guardian reported
today.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,000 out of 8,000 passengers who were travelling by
rail to the northwest region of Mwanza have been forced to return
to Dar es Salaam after the portion between Ipala and Bukene in
the neighboring region Tabora was washed away by floods.
</P>
<P>
The passengers had been stranded for 48 hours at Tabora
Station and Tanzania Railways Corporation (TRC) officials said
here Friday that it would take engineers seven days to to repair
the damaged portion of the railway.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that so many passengers were stranded at
the station, TRC officials said.
</P>
<P>
In Igunga and Nzega districts, heavy rains destroyed some 150
houses leaving hundreds of people homeless, the Nzega District
Commissioner, said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Road services between Tabora and Mbeya regions have been
suspended after the Ipole bridge was washed away by floods, the
Sikonge District Commissioner, Ms Beatrice Mkina said.
</P>
<P>
In Kilosa District, Morogoro Region, floods damaged more than
200 houses leaving over 1,000 people homeless.
</P>
<P>
The Kilosa District Commissioner, Ms Eddy Tumbo, said that
floods seriously affected Mtendeni and Magomeni areas in Kilosa
town and Madizini village.
</P>
<P>
A district task force has been formed to evaluate the loss
incurred and to look for ways to prevent further floods.
</P>
<P>
She said people whose houses have been damaged by the floods
have taken refuge in primary schools. Others are living in with
their relatives.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Musoma said Friday more than 20 families were
vacating their houses which are about to be engulfed by floods,
and 10 houses have been damaged by the floods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
