<HEADLINE> Asian-European Soccer Bridge Set from 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 13 (Xinhua) -- Asian football's European
connections will be strengthened up as a between-continental
contest involving top Asian teams and European powerhouses such as
Germany and Italy will be carried out annually from 1999 after
next year's World Cup
</P>
<P>
Asia will send six teams to play against as many European
counterparts on a home-and-away basis every year since 1999, Dato'
Peter Velappan, General Secretary of Asian Football Confederation
(AFC) declared at a news conference here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
AFC are currently discussing with the football associations
from England, the Netherlands, France, Germany, Italy and Spain to
make possible Asian soccer can regularly get in touch with world's
best soccer to boost its own levels.
</P>
<P>
Five of the six Asian participants have been settled down and
they are four next year World Cup finalists, namely South Korea,
Iran, Japan and Saudi Arabia, plus China, he revealed.
</P>
<P>
The last team to grab the appealing opportunity to play up with
European big names will come from West Asian Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Yogoslavia or Croatia would be other European possibilities, Dr.
Velappan said.
</P>
<P>
Reactions from the European side were "very receptive", and they
have recognized the growing-up of Asian football and would help to
internationize the growth and the development, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"It's a good year for Asian football in 1997, " the general
secretary said, "Four of our teams have qualified for World Cup
next year in France and they have been grouped in company of
European giants.
</P>
<P>
"Fifteen of the thirty-two qualified teams come from Europe and
that's why I'm always suggesting we should play more games with
the Europeans."
</P>
<P>
AFC has its next project to develop Asian football in
cooperation with Africa, Dr. Velappan said.
</P>
<P>
Also from 1999, top two Asian under-20 youth teams will play
against their African counterparts on an annual basis, and similar
arrangements with the European youth teams will be set out from
the year of 2000, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
