<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nanjing Massacre Documentary Film Discovered in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, December 13 (Xinhua) -- A documentary film on Nanjing
Massacre that had never been released, was discovered in the
United States, said Tze-ping Shao, first head of a U.S.-based
association in commemoration of Nanjing Massacre victims.
</P>
<P>
The six-week long Nanjing Massacre started 60 years ago today
during which some 300,000 civilians and disarmed Chinese soldiers
were killed by the intruding Japanese troops.
</P>
<P>
Shao, a Chinese-American, said here Friday in an interview with
Xinhua that the 37-minute soundless black-white documentary film
was shot by John Gillespie Magee, a US missionary in China from
1912 to 1940 who died in 1953.
</P>
<P>
Magee, who had been chairman of the Nanjing International Red
Cross Society, used a 16-mm. camera to take scenes of Japanese
soldiers killing, raping or robbing Nanjing civilians in Ginling
University Hospital and other places in the city during late 1937
and 1938, Shao noted.
</P>
<P>
In late 1938, Shao added, Magee's colleague named George
A. Fitch, brought the first part of the documentary to Shanghai at
the risk of his life and made four copies after editing and
entitling the film.
</P>
<P>
Then, Fitch and Magee kept two copies each.
</P>
<P>
The documentary film was mentioned in Bates Documents, left by
Miner Bates, who was in Nanjing for the 30 years preceding 1950.
</P>
<P>
A German diplomat also mentioned the documentary film in his
report submitted to the German Foreign Ministry on February 10,
1938, saying that "the narration of the scenes and the film itself
is a very stunning document."
</P>
<P>
The documentary film had not been discovered till 1990.
</P>
<P>
After an announcement for collecting Nanjing Massacre related
materials made by Shao in New York Times in 1990 publicized,
Fitch's daughter Edith offered her father's film copy and
recollections, and David, Magee's son, found his father's positive
at the basement of his house.
</P>
<P>
David recalled that he had first seen the film in 1938 when he
accompanied his father to London and the documentary film was kept
at his home afterwards.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971213.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
