<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 12 COMESA Members Under Sanctions for Failure to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 13 (Xinhua) -- Twelve out of 20 members of
the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) are
under sanctions for failure to contribute to the budget for two
or more years, Times of Zambia reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a report from the Lusaka-based organization
as saying that the unprecedented move against the defaulting members
including Angola, Democratic Republic of Congo, Ethiopia, Malawi,
Mozambique and Tanzania, is in accordance with the COMESA Treaty
signed in 1994 which calls for sanctions against members that
fail to meet their obligations to the regional body.
</P>
<P>
Twelve are affected by the decision to have all benefits and
operations suspended in those countries and to lose rights and
privileges, including addressing policy organs' meetings.
</P>
<P>
The suspension of operations are to cover all new
extra-budgetary resources' projects, except those currently being
implemented, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The second part of the sancitons states that all the arrears
as at the end of 1997 will accrue one percent interest which will
be reflected in the assessment for the 1998 financial year.
</P>
<P>
Nationals of the affected countries will cease to be eligible
for new recruitment to COMESA staff, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the sanctions imposed on the 12 members can only
be lifted only after the apropriate payments are made.
</P>
<P>
Up to November 21, the COMESA secretariat has received 3.49
million dollars representing 76 percent of the 1997 budget
of 4.6 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the same date, arrears in contributions by member states
stood at about 8.52 million dollars or about two financial years'
COMESA budgets, said the report, adding that to date only three
members are fully paid up. 
</P>
