<HEADLINE> U.S., China Initial Pact on Prevention of Naval Incidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Senior U.S. and Chinese
defense officials Saturday initialed an agreement designed to
prevent naval accidents at sea as they ended the first-ever formal
defense consultations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Maritime Military Consultative Agreement was worked out
during Chinese President Jiang Zemin's visit to Washington in
October.
</P>
<P>
The two-day defense talks also yielded an agreement on
exchanging information on their military's role in humanitarian
relief missions.
</P>
<P>
The talks at the Pentagon were led by Walter Slocombe, U.S.
Under-Secretary of Defense and visiting Chinese Lt. General Xiong
Guangkai, deputy chief of the general staff of the People's
Liberation Army. The two sides exchanged views on a wide range of
issues, including international and regional security, and
discussed exchange programs between the two armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Xiong also had talks with U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen,
both agreeing that the formal defense consultations were a
concrete step toward the establishing of a 21st century oriented
strategic partnership between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after the consultations, the Pentagon
said Slocombe would visit China next year as part of a plan to
regularize high-level defense meetings. Cohen is also scheduled to
visit Beijing next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
