<HEADLINE> WTO, EU Leaders Hope for China's Early Entry into WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 13 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) and the European Union (EU) voiced their hope
Sunday that China will join the WTO as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference following the reaching of the Agreement
on Financial Services, WTO Director-General Renato Ruggiero said
he shares the wish that China will be, in the next two years, a
member of the WTO and it "will participate in the negotiation or
the process of the liberalization by making a good offer."
</P>
<P>
"We believe that this will be very much in the interest of
China because China will enjoy also, through the participation of
foreign banks and foreign insurance companies, the benefits in its
process of the strengthening of the financial institutions,"
Ruggiero said.
</P>
<P>
China has now had no say in the negotiations to liberalize
trade in financial services as it is not a WTO member.
</P>
<P>
At the 6th session of the Working Party on China's Accession to
the WTO, China's vice foreign trade minister Long Yongtu expressed
China's hope to participate, as a full member of the WTO, in the
next round of negotiations on trade in services which begin on
January 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
"We also share the hope that China will at the earlier possible
date become a member of the WTO," said European Commission Vice
President Sir Leon Brittan.
</P>
<P>
"I was in China a couple of months ago, and had very good talks
with Chinese leaders," he recalled. "We've reached agreement on a
set of principles which, I think, will narrow the area of the
negotiation on China's membership of the WTO."
</P>
<P>
"I hope we can build on that by dealing with some of the other
areas such as services, and in this way make progress toward the
final agreement," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
