<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Agreement on Financial Services Hailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 13 (Xinhua) -- The successful conclusion of
negotiations on financial services today has made 1997 a golden
year of the international trading system, said Renato Ruggiero,
Director-General of the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
"This landmark agreement comes at a critical time," Ruggiero
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"With so much of the world facing economic turbulence,
negotiators from all our members have shown once again the courage
and commitment to pursue the policies of liberalization which are
essential to economic stability, growth and development," he
said.
</P>
<P>
With the Agreement on Financial Services, the WTO has reached
three agreements of historic importance in a year. It reached the
Agreement on Basic Telecommunications Services on February 15 and
the Information Technology Agreement on March 26.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read by Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Jeffrey
Lang, U.S. President Bill Clinton said, "Today's agreement by 70
countries (and regions) to liberalize trade in financial services
will ensure market access in sectors where we lead the
world: banking, securities, and insurance."
</P>
<P>
"In the wake of recent financial instability, it is
particularly encouraging that so many countries have chosen to
move forward rather than backward," said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, European Commission Vice President Sir
Leon Brittan said that the agreement would provide opportunities
for providers of financial services all over the world to increase
their activities.
</P>
<P>
"It is important to reach this agreement at the moment because
it will be a sign of the capacity of the world to reach the
agreement with the participation of the countries in Asia,"
Brittan said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that it will provide a source of confidence in that
part of the world," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971213.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Political Parties Turn Cautious on Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 13 (Xinhua)-- The mood among political
parties has been one of caution towards economic reforms, local
newspaper Business Standard said here today.
</P>
<P>
While they acknowledged the importance and necessity of
economic reforms, they were clear it would not be at the cost of
the industry.
All political parties agreed there was no need for further
reduction in the tax rates.
</P>
<P>
Jay Dubashi, part of the think-tank of the Bharatiya Janata
Party (BJP), the biggest opposition party in the country, on
economic issues, said, "I don't see any more scope for reduction
of tax as ours is comparable with rates in other Asian countries."
</P>
<P>
Congress Working Committee member Pranab Mukherjee and
politburo member of the Communist Party of India Prakash Karat
said that they wanted the existing tax base to be widened.
</P>
<P>
On the much-talked about insurance sector reforms, the BJP and
the Congress gave almost similar views -- they welcomed Indian
private sector participation but would not accept foreign
investors in the area. The Left completely opposed privatization
of the sector.
</P>
<P>
On capital account convertibility, Congress leader Pranab
Mukherjee said, "We should move cautiously in this area. We should
not take any hasty decision." The BJP is also for a cautious
approach towards capital account convertibility. Dubashi said that
if there was any hasty decision on the issue the country would
face the same fate as other South Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
In their recent summit, the World Economic Forum and the
Confederation of Indian Industry have put up some recommendations
which included reduction in tax rates, opening up of the insurance
sector to foreign investors, and full capital account
convertibility.  
</P>
</TEXT>
