<DOCNO> XIE19971213.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Banks to Change Tack on Gold Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 13 (Xinhua)-- India's commercial banks
licensed to import gold are planning to source the yellow metal on
a consignment basis, wherein no purchase price is truck up front,
to hedge against future volatility in domestic prices, bank
sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
Though they did not burn their fingers in bullion operations
during the past month which was characterized by a steady fall in
prices, the move is to ensure complete insulation from price
fluctuations, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The slide in domestic gold prices has been triggered by the
Reserve Bank of India (RBI) decision in October this year to free
gold import restrictions in the country.
</P>
<P>
With gold import being freed, domestic gold prices are
vulnerable. Banks are moving towards sourcing gold in consignments
and preparing the ground for it.
</P>
<P>
"In such a transaction, the foreign supplier entrusts the gold
with us, and the price is fixed when the buyer comes in," the same
sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971213.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
