<HEADLINE> Thailand Gets Aid for Child Labor Elimination Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 13 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has signed an
agreement with the International Program for the Elimination of
Child Labor (IPEC), under which Thailand will get 86,000 U.S.
dollars in grant for teachers training.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used to train 164 primary school teachers in
82 rural schools in the prevention and resolution of child labor
abuse.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that teachers play a vital role in spotting,
dissuading and solving the problem of younger teenagers entering
the labor market.
</P>
<P>
The aim of IPEC is to end child labor and abuse by attacking
the root causes -- poverty, and lack of education opportunities
and reliable information on employment.
</P>
<P>
According to an IPEC study, 60 percent of the estimated 250
million under-aged workers worldwide are in Asia. In Thailand, 70
percent of child labor is employed in agriculture, and the
remainder in the industry and service sectors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
