<DOCNO> XIE19971213.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Planning Board Sees Economic Recovery in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 13 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's overall economy
will recover in 1999, according to a senior official of the
National Economic and Social Development Board.
</P>
<P>
Wirat Wattanasiritham, secretary general of the country's
national planning board, predicted Friday that Thailand would
achieve economic growth and an inflation rate of 4 percent in
1999-2001.
</P>
<P>
He based his forecast on an exchange rate of between 35 to 36
baht to the U.S. dollar, according to the local press today.
</P>
<P>
However, the forecast might not be viable as the baht already
crashed past the 45 barrier to close at 45.65 to the dollar
Friday, losing about 77 percent of its value to the dollar since
the baht was floated five months ago at 25.79.
</P>
<P>
Wirat said despite the economic problems, the country could
compete internationally in agriculture, canned food and service
sectors.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the government should not make more cuts in
the national budget as it will hamper the national economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
He advised instead that the government improve tax collection.
</P>
<P>
In its latest review of the economic growth, released Friday,
the board predicted that the growth rate for the current fiscal
year (October 1, 1997 to September 30, 1998) would be zero.
</P>
</TEXT>
