<HEADLINE> People's Savings at Myanmar State Bank Reach 60B Kyats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 13 (Xinhua) -- People's savings at the
state-owned Myanmar Economic Bank (MEB) reached nearly 60 billion
kyats (about 200 million U.S. dollars), according to a senior
Myanmar finance official.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting of the MEB here Friday, Win Tin, minister
for finance and revenue, also disclosed that the bank disbursed
loans amounting to 31 billion kyats (about 103.3 million U.S.
dollars) as of October, official newspaper The New Light of
Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister pointed out, the disbursement of loans
was only 51 percent of the savings, stressing the need to seek
means to increase its earning.
</P>
<P>
The minister called for improvement of services of the state
bank to be able to compete with private counterparts.
</P>
<P>
There are six state-run banks in Myanmar, and 25 private banks
have been added since the country reformed its financial
management system in line with the market-oriented economy
introduced in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, people's savings at banks in
Myanmar totaled 88.217 billion kyats (about 294 million U.S.
dollars) in the 1996-97 fiscal year which ended in March. Of
these, savings at state-run banks accounted for 62 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a total of 48 representative offices of foreign
banks have also been set up in the country, and some of them plan
to establish joint ventures with local banks in light of Myanmar's
entry into the second phase of its financial reform.  
</P>
</TEXT>
