<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rustling, Extortion Cost Colombian Cattlemen $749 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Colombia lost 749
billion pesos (some 749 million U.S. dollars) in the first 11
months of this year due to the country's insecurity in
cattle-related activities, the National Cattlemen's Association
(Fedegan) said today.
</P>
<P>
The Fedegan said that as of November 1997, 73 cattlemen were
killed in 410 kidnappings. The kidnapped cattlemen were forced to
pay 73.8 billion pesos (73.8 million U.S. dollars) in ransom.
</P>
<P>
It said 38,482 cattlemen were victims of extortion in 1997. The
losses rose to more than 92 billion pesos (about 92 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
At the same time, 95,000 head of cattle valued at around 37
billion pesos (37 million dollars) were stolen.
</P>
<P>
The cattlemen also lost 545 billion pesos (545 million dollars)
by not being able to properly maintain their ranches due to
problems related to the lack of security.
</P>
<P>
Cattle raising makes up 5 percent of the Colombian gross
domestic product (GDP) and 60 percent of the livestock sector, the
Fedegan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
