<HEADLINE> Moldova Collects Weightlifting Titles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHIANG MAI, Northern Thailand, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Moldova
won its first two gold medals at the World Weightlifting
Championships while new world records were set by strongwomen from
Turkey and China here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Tadeusz Drzazga of Poland won the first gold in the men's
91-kilogram category with a lift of 177.5 kilograms in the snatch,
with Vadim Vacarciuc of Moldova and Maksim Agapitov of Russia both
lifting 175.0 kgs.
</P>
<P>
Vacarciuc took the silver on the favour of his lighter weight,
then claimed the victory in the clean and jerk in 212.5 kgs. Julio
Luna of Venezuela carried the same bar but had to settle with the
silver medal due to his heavier body weight.
</P>
<P>
With a total lift of 387.5 kgs, Vacarciuc claimed his second
golds, while the total silver went to Turkish Sunay Bulut for
382.5 kgs and Russian Agapitov for 380.0 kgs.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 76 kg class, 17-year-old Aysel Ozgur captured a
gold for Turkey in the snatch with a new world record lift of
110.0 kgs, and won the silver for the total with her aggregate of
235.0 kgs.
</P>
<P>
Hua Ju of China, who took the silver in the snatch with a lift
of 107.5 kgs, set a world record in capturing the gold in the
clean and jerk in 140.5 kgs.
</P>
<P>
The total gold went to Hua with 247.5 kgs, which was also a new
world record, 12.5 kgs better than the previous mark.
</P>
<P>
Maria Takacs of Hungary, capturing the bronze in the snatch
with 100.0 kgs and second bronze for the clean and jerk with a
125.0 kgs, earned her the third bronze with an total of 225.0
kgs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
