<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Insurance Company of China Taps Foreign Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 13 (Xinhua) -- The People's Insurance Company
of China (Group) will focus on exploring the insurance business
in Southeast Asia, which was hit by the the financial crisis
recently.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily quote Wu Xiaping, vice-president of the
group as saying that his group is planning to set up in Singapore
its Southeast Asia Regional Office to coordinate its activities.
</P>
<P>
Wu added that the insurance group is going to made a
feasibility study on launching companies in Malaysia and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president said that the financial turmoil, which has
has slowed down economic growth, reduced income and raised the
unemployment rate in Southeast Asia, would have surely resulted in
a negative impact on the local insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
He said the sharp devaluation of the local currency will
increase costs to insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
Wu noted that although the negative influence may last some
years, he still believes that the region has a bright future after
it solves the problems that emerged in this financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
He explained that it is easier for the group to explore the
Southeast Asia market as the overseas Chinese living there provide
a rich resource to tap.
</P>
<P>
The group has already set up two branches in Singapore an a
joint venture in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Ma Yongwei, president of the group, said that they will further
explore South Pacific regions where the group has established a
company in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
He said his group will also choose an appropriate time to enter
the Middle East, South Africa, South American and Eastern European
markets.
</P>
<P>
He believed that these markets have great potential although
they are not well developed.
</P>
<P>
The premium income of existing overseas affiliates in 1996
rose by 39.7 percent from 1994, while the after-tax profits of
these affiliates rose 72.4 percent in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
