<DOCNO> XIE19971213.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Parliament Approves 1998 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The Bulgarian National Assembly
(parliament) passed the "financial constitution" for next year, or
the 1998 national budget on Friday.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that Bulgaria has approved a budget
before the end of the calendar year.
</P>
<P>
The budget revenue is estimated at 3.56 trillion leva (about
2.22 billion U.S. dollars), while proceeds from the sale of
intangible assets and concessions are projected at 20.2 billion
leva (about 12.8 million dollars), according to the constitution.
</P>
<P>
The budget expenditures are set at 4.17 trillion leva (about
2.61 billion dollars) of which 1 trillion leva (about 625.8
million dollars) are internal and external debt payments.
</P>
<P>
The defense and security budget is 25.6 billion leva (about
15.9 million dollars) that will be spent in compliance with the
schedule for restructuring the Bulgarian Army.
</P>
<P>
A total of 299 billion leva (about 16 million dollars) will be
spent for wages in the state-financed sectors. The subsidy for the
judiciary is 40.5 billion leva (about 25.3 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit is restricted within 610.8 trillion leva
(about 382.2 million dollars). It will be financed by external
and internal loans, transactions in government securities and
privatization proceeds, expected to be about 540 trillion leva
(about 337.9 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government may issue bonds for external capital markets in
the amount of 200 million dollars and use the proceeds for
restructuring the national debt to facilitate its servicing
without increasing it.
</P>
<P>
A special provision in the law authorizes the government to
negotiate and sign agreements with the G-24 countries for loans in
the amount of 50 million dollars, or their equivalent in another
currency, in a balance of payments support.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Mouravei Radev hopes the budget will not be
updated. He said over 50 proposals by MPs have been taken into
consideration in drafting the budget.
</P>
<P>
Economist Stefan Stoilov, a member of parliament, said the
budget spells freezing real-term incomes. Finance Ministry
calculations showed there is an increase of 0.5 to 0.75 percent of
real-term incomes and a 1.3 decrease of real-term pensions next
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
