<HEADLINE> Siemens, Mercedes-Benz Expand Investments in Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The big German firms,
Siemens and Mercedes-Benz, have expressed a plan to expand their
investments in Brazil in the coming years, according to local
press reports Friday.
</P>
<P>
Siemens President Heinrich von Pierer said the group is very
optimistic about its investment and growth in Brazil, even after
the Brazilian government took measures to readjust economically to
face the effects of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Von Pierer said Siemens will transfer investments worth 100
million U.S. dollars to Brazil in the next two years. He is
confident the strategy of the Brazilian consortium would not be
affected by short term problems.
</P>
<P>
The German Mercedes-Benz firm announced Thursday that it will
begin investing immediately until the year 2000 a total investment
of one billion dollars in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The firm, according to the Mercedes-Benz announcement for next
year, will direct 600 million dollars to its factories in Brazil,
100 million of which will be used to modernize the existing
assembly line for the production of heavy vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Another 500 million will be invested in the on-going
construction of a motor vehicle factory in the city of Juiz de
Fora, in the state of Minas Gerais, which is scheduled to start
production next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
