<HEADLINE> CAAC to Update Its Computer System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 13 (Xinhua) -- The computer center of the
Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC) has signed a
contract with the US-based Unisys Corporation to introduce a
state-of-the-art computer system that can handle 200 million
travelers a year, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The 15-million-US-dollar Unisys Clearpath 8-CPU System, and 1.8
million US dollars worth of data communication processors, will
allow expansion and optimization of the CAAC's passenger inventory
control system, the paper quoted Xie Qingling, an official with
the CAAC computer center, as saying.
</P>
<P>
China's civil aviation business has been soaring by 20.1
percent annually during the past 15 years, and last year more than
55 million people traveled by air in China.
</P>
<P>
Xie told China Daily that his center's current network and
systems are unable to cope with the expanding market.
</P>
<P>
The new system, with a large-capacity computer, is expected to
arrive in Beijing later this month, and will begin trial
operations in May, Xie said. 
</P>
