<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT December 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG -- European Union (EU) leaders Friday decided to
establish a euro council in order to manage the planned single
currency and to expand eastward to include the 10 eastern European
candidates and Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state and government of 15 EU member countries
Friday made the decision after marathon talks on the first day of
the two-day EU summit held in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
The euro council is expected to be an informal and
non-decision-making organization which will be responsible for
coordinating the economic and budgetary policies of euro countries
after the planned economic and monetary union (EMU) is launched in
January 1999. (EU Summit in Luxembourg)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- A tank with 4,000 cubic meters (264,200
gallons) of oil caught fire Friday when a thunderbolt hit the
Yacimientos Petroliferos Fiscales (YPF) refinery in the province
of Mendoza, in the west of Argentina.
</P>
<P>
Several firefighting teams were working to suffocate the fire.
</P>
<P>
No victims had been registered so far, said refinery labor
relations director Alejandro Gareschi. (Argentine Oil Refinery on
Fire)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Germany's economy would continue its current upswing
and would expect a 2.6-percent growth in 1998, the Ifo economic
research institute predicted Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Munich-based institute, the increase in GDP
next year would be driven by a continued export boom as well as a
modest recovery in the domestic economy.
</P>
<P>
However, it also warned that the country's economy still lacks
a solid footing and is likely to be negatively affected by the
recent financial crisis in Asia. (German Economy up 2.6 Percent)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- Ghanaian police have arrested 14 people since a
sectarian clash began in the northwestern town of Wa three days
ago, a police source said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Late on Wednesday in Wa, 500 km northwest of the capital Accra,
members of the Tijaniya Moslem sect attacked the property of the
Al-Sunni sect after provoking preachings by the latter group, the
source said.
</P>
<P>
By Thursday morning, seven houses, a Mosque, a junior secondary
school, an Arabic school, kiosks and stores belonging to the
Al-Sunni were completely burnt down and their contents destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The car of the regional minister and a police jeep were also
damaged, the source said, quoted by a report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The attack took place despite warning shot by the police while
troops of the army's airborne force have been deployed in the
town, where they have restored order, the report said. (Armed
Clash in Ghana)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Germany's parliament Friday decided to launch a special
probe into a series of neo-Nazi scandals that have seriously
damaged the image of the German armed forces, the Bundeswehr.
</P>
<P>
The probe, insisted by the German opposition parties, the
Social Democratic Party (SPD) and the Greens, will start next
January with the establishment of a parliamentary investigation
committee.
</P>
<P>
The move was prompted mainly by a major scandal a week ago
after a convicted neo-Nazi, Manfred Roeder, was found to have been
invited to deliver a speech in 1995 to a German military academy
training top officers. (Germany Probes Neo-Nazi) 
</P>
