<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Currency Crisis of Little Concern to Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The high quality of Italian
produced goods means that Mediterranean country has no reason to
fear the ongoing financial crisis in southeast Asia, Italian
Foreign Trade Minister Augusto Fantozzi said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The characteristics of Italian foreign trade allow us not to
be too concerned about the crisis," Fantozzi said a day after
fragile Asian stock markets plummeted again, raising new fears of
a slump in the regional economy.
</P>
<P>
Falling demand in Southeast Asia affects Italy less than other
countries, the minister said, because Italy's exports are
primarily of quality goods whose appeal usually holds up in times
of crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said quality would also be a key factor when regional
consumers came to choose between Italian goods and local
equivalents made cheaper by currency devaluation.
</P>
<P>
On Italian imports from Southeast Asia, the severe devaluation
of the Korean won could make Korea's car industry more
competitive here, Fantozzi said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that Italy was also shielded from the crisis in
Southeast Asia because only 6 percent of its goods were exported
to those Asian countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
