<HEADLINE> Beijing Newspaper Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 13 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin, in a Friday meeting with Takuhiko
Tsuruta, president of Nihon Keizai Shimbun, and his party, urged
the Japanese to draw a lesson from history for the sustained and
healthy development of Sino-Japanese relations. Today is the 60th
anniversary of the Nanjing Massacre, in which the Japanese
intruding troops slaughtered over 300,000 Chinese civilians and
unarmed soldiers after their capture of the eastern China city of
Nanjing, then the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Li Peng told visiting Uzbekistan Foreign Minister
Kamilov Abdulaziz Hafizovich yesterday in Beijing that China feels
satisfied with the development of Sino-Uzbekistan relations. China
and Uzbekistan forged their diplomatic ties six years ago.
</P>
<P>
Li also met with visiting Fijian Minister of Foreign Affairs
and Trade Berenado Vunibobo yesterday.
</P>
<P>
-- The State Council, China's cabinet, convened yesterday its
64th executive meeting, at which the Regulations on the Management
of Slaughtering Pigs was deliberated and approved.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin said yesterday in Beijing that his
recent visit to the United States has yielded important results
and the world welcomes the improvement of Sino-US relations.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remarks while meeting with Admiral Joseph
Prueher, Commander-in-Chief of the US Pacific Command.
</P>
<P>
-- Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji, also a Standing Committee member of
the Political Bureau of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central
Committee, praised yesterday in Beijing the Bank of China and the
People's Insurance Company of China for their successful overseas
operations.
</P>
<P>
-- Hu Jintao, a member of the Standing Committee of the CPC
Central Committee's Political Bureau, said that the people of
China and Mongolia have a tradition of friendly feelings towards
each other during a meeting with a Mongolian National Democratic
Party delegation led by its vice-president Bat-uul yesterday in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
-- Wei Jianxing, a member of the Standing Committee of the
Political Bureau and member of the Secretariat of the CPC Central
Committee, left Beijing Friday on a goodwill visit to India.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Li Ruihuan, chairman of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference National Committee, said yesterday in
Wellington at a meeting with Michael Hardie Boys, governor-general
of New Zealand, that broad prospects for the growth of economic
cooperation and trade between China and New Zealand exist on the
basis of equality and mutual benefit as the two economies are
complementary with each other.
</P>
<P>
Li, who arrived on Thursday, is on a four-day official goodwill
visit to New Zealand at the invitation of the New Zealand
government.
</P>
<P>
-- Beijing Party Secretary Jia Qinglin said that the Chinese
capital will march into the 21st century with new images for both
its urban development and its people's living standard. Jia made
the pledge in a work report to the Eighth Beijing Municipal Party
Congress, which opened Friday.
</P>
<P>
-- A forum was held in Beijing on Thursday to mark the 60th
anniversary of the Nanjing Massacre. Scholars and officials
present at the forum said that attempts by Japanese right wingers
to cover the truth of the massacre must be exposed and that the
Chinese must remember the event to promote patriotism.  
</P>
