<HEADLINE> Bank of China Eyes Further Growth in Oversea Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 13 (Xinhua) -- Bank of China (BOC) prepares
to establish its branches in Malaysia, Italy, the United States
and Brazil in the near future.
</P>
<P>
According to China Daily today, the BOC has set up 546 overseas
affiliates in 22 countries and regions by the end of October.
</P>
<P>
Heads of the bank's overseas affiliates gather in Beijing
Friday to attend a five-day meeting during which they will draft
the development strategy for the next century.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted BOC President Wang Xuebing as saying that his
bank has witnessed sound advances in globalization. He added that
the deposits of the oversea affiliates rose 26.1 percent over 1995
and the average assets of oversea branches during the past 10
months of this year rose 9 percent of the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
BOC opened branches in Zimbabwe and Viet Nam in the past two
years while opening a representative office in Hungary, he noted,
adding that an investment bank was also established in Britain
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
He said BOC has enhanced overseas affiliates in Africa,
Southeast Asia, Latin America and Eastern Europe in accordance
with the country's foreign trade development and diplomatic
policies.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the bank president said, the overseas affiliates have
adopted various ways to pool foreign capital in support of the
development of the domestic energy, transportation,
telecommunications and raw material sectors while helping the
Chinese-invested firms in foreign countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
