<HEADLINE> Clinton Reportedly Nearing Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
is said to be nearing a decision to appoint Bill Lann Lee the
government's chief civil rights lawyer.
</P>
<P>
White House aides reportedly said they had discussed the option
of Clinton's simply naming Lee to the job at the opening of his
scheduled news conference on Monday. The so-called recess
appointment would mean Lee could serve until the end of the next
session of Congress.
</P>
<P>
But White House spokesman Mike McCurry said, "The president
hasn't made any final decision on that because the president would
prefer to see him confirmed."
</P>
<P>
Word circulated on Capitol Hill that Clinton would indeed make
the appointment on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Lee, 48, has made clear that he will accept if Clinton decides
to appoint him to head the Justice Department's civil rights
division. He told an interviewer he would do so out of concern
that the nation's civil rights laws be enforced.
</P>
<P>
"So if the president asked me to take that job and make sure
that the law enforcement job gets done,... I would really look
forward to doing what I could," Lee said on NBC's "Today" program.
</P>
<P>
Critics say Lee's support of affirmative action makes him unfit
for the job.
</P>
<P>
If appointed or confirmed, Lee would become the first
Asian-American to hold the civil rights post in its 40-year
history.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said that Clinton won't decide on a recess appointment
"until he is absolutely certain" there is no other way to put Lee
in the job." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971213.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Leaders Decide on Euro Council, Enlargement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, December 12 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) leaders
today decided to establish a euro council in order to manage the
planned single currency and to expand eastward to include the 10
eastern European candidates and Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state and government of 15 EU member countries
Friday made the decision after marathon talks on the first day of
the two-day EU summit held in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
The euro council is expected to be an informal and
non-decision-making organization which will be responsible for
coordinating the economic and budgetary policies of euro countries
after the planned economic and monetary union (EMU) is launched in
January 1999.
</P>
<P>
It was decided that euro countries would be entitled to get
together to discuss problems concerning themselves and that it
might be possible to invite the non-euro countries to attend if
there were issues of common interest to be raised.
</P>
<P>
Britain has announced that it will not join EMU before 2002.
Sweden, Denmark and Greece have also decided to stay out at the
time when EMU will be formally launched.
</P>
<P>
However, all the decisions will only be taken at meetings of
finance ministers from the 15 EU member countries.
</P>
<P>
"This is a little bit unexpected," said French Finance Minister
Dominique Strauss-Kahn after the agreement was reached.
</P>
<P>
Britain and France had a fierce row over a French proposal to
create a special council for the inner circle of countries
planning to be in the first wave of EU member countries joining
EMU at its launch.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac told Britain's Tony Blair
during talks Friday that he must compromise if he wanted an
agreement. "He asked for an effort from Britain if it wanted a
deal," Chirac's spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
The EU leaders also agreed Friday to launch its enlargement
process with the 10 eastern European countries and Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
It was decided that the entry talks would be started first with
five-plus-one configuration recommended in July by the European
Commission, the EU's executive body, early next year.
</P>
<P>
The configuration is composed by Poland, Hungary, the Czech
Republic, Slovenia, Estonia and Cyprus, six countries the EU
considers to be advanced in both political and economic terms.
</P>
<P>
The other five applicants, Bulgaria, Romania, Lithuania, Latvia
and Slovakia, will also begin early next year to participate in
the enlargement process but have to be patient before they can
have truly entry talks with the EU.
</P>
<P>
The five candidates, which will take part in the "entry
partnerships" like the others, will be assessed on the basis of
their progress to see if they are qualified to join the entry
talks.
</P>
<P>
EU leaders agreed that annual meetings between leaders of these
countries and the EU would take place to evaluate their progress.
The EU noted that the entry negotiations could last some ten years
for certain candidates.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, however, was excluded from the enlargement process
though it was the first candidate which has been applying for EU
membership since 1963. Turkey was accused of failing to satisfy
the EU's political criteria, such as improved human rights record
and respect of democracy.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the EU also accused Ankara of lack of efforts to
improve its relations with neighboring country Greece, which has
long been firmly opposed to Turkey becoming an EU member.
</P>
<P>
Frustrated with the exclusion, Turkey Friday turned down an EU
invitation to dine with its leaders on Saturday after the summit
is closed.
</P>
<P>
In spite of Turkey's rejection, the EU leaders still agreed
that it was politically difficult to exclude Turkey from the
"European family."
</P>
<P>
France, backed up by Germany, has proposed a European
conference which will group all the eleven EU candidate and Turkey
in order to discuss issues of common interest as a configuration
of 15 plus 12.
</P>
<P>
A European conference lacks substance if Turkey is not
attending, according to EU Commissioner Hans van den Broek.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971213.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-13 </DATE_TIME>
