<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Emergency Post-Conflict Aid to Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today approved a credit for Rwanda equivalent to some 8
million U.S. dollars, under the IMF's policy of emergency
post-conflict assistance.
</P>
<P>
The previous credit under the same policy of about 12 million
dollars equivalent was approved by the institution on April 22
this year to support the government's economic program for 1997.
</P>
<P>
The major objectives of the program were to attain a real GDP
growth rate of 12.7 percent, an inflation rate of 7 percent, and a
level of gross official international reserves equivalent to 4.4
months of imports.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda joined the IMF in September 1963. Its quota is about 80
million dollars and its outstanding use of IMF financing currently
totals about 34 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
