<HEADLINE> U.S. Urged to Help Southeast Asian Countries Weather Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Former Deputy U.S. Trade
Representative Robert D. Hormats today called on the U.S.
government to rethink about the impact of Southeast Asian
financial turmoil and give bail-out support to the region.
</P>
<P>
He made the appeal at an Asia Society-sponsored conference on
"Tigers" in Transition to analyze the financial difficulties in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Indonesian Finance Minister Mar'ie Muhammad's
keynote address to the conference, Hormats said the Administration
needs "to do a lot of selling" to Congress and the American public
to underscore the needs of U.S. support to the region.
</P>
<P>
He said the signal that the United States has so far given to
the region is that "there is no American money", and that the U.S.
"is really pulling back from responsibilities" in the notion that
each region should take care of its own financial problems.
</P>
<P>
He said there seems much "inward-looking view" among some
members of the Congress that the financial problems in Southeast
Asia do not affect much on them or that the money should be spent
at home.
</P>
<P>
Actually the wave "has begun to wash out on our own shores", he
said, referring to recent New York Stock Exchange's downturn
partly due to the psychological impact stemmed from the weakening
performance of some U.S. firms in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The crisis in the region is not wholly regional and there is no
substitute to the approach of the U.S. except encouraging the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) to lend more support or taking
its own initiative in this direction, Hormats said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
