<HEADLINE> Business Costs in Western Countries Higher than in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Developing countries have lower
business operating costs than western countries for international
investment, the Financial Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Citing a survey of costs in 27 countries by the Economist
Intelligence Unit (EIU), the newspaper said that business in
industrialized nations incur far higher wage and infrastructure
costs than in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that in general, nations in southeast Asia are
between 10 and 60 times cheaper for business than western
countries.
</P>
<P>
The countries surveyed include those which had attracted
significant inward investments and others with the potential to
woo foreign companies in the future.
</P>
<P>
The study, which is based on wages and employers' costs, office
and industrial rents, telecommunications, corporate taxes,
expatriate costs, business travel and corruption, found that
Germany is the most expensive of the countries surveyed, with a
relative score of 100.
</P>
<P>
Then come the US, with 91.8 and Belgium with 89.4.
</P>
<P>
However, Thailand, Malaysia and Indonesia all score less than
six, and South Africa has the lowest score of only one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
