<HEADLINE> U.S. Secretary of State Visits Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright said here today that the Angolan Peace
Process is now approaching an end, but certain tasks stipulated
in the peace agreement are still unaccomplished.
</P>
<P>
Albright made the statement during her brief visit here in
Angola after her visit in the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
She expressed regret that Jonas Savimbi, chairman of the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA)
failed to come to Luanda for the meeting and appealed to the
former rebel movement to shift its headquarters to Luanda, or
risk the danger of being excluded from political life.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of state started her visit in Angola at
noon. Before she reached Luanda, Albright had visited Cabinda,
an oil-producing area in northern Angola where she met with the
country's Minister of Petroleum Albina Assis.
</P>
<P>
In a speech delivered in Cabinda, she said the United States
enjoys good cooperation with Angola in the field of petroleum.
U.S. oil import from Angola had accounted for seven percent of
its total import, almost four times its import volume from
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. will further its economic cooperation with Angola,
she said, adding the U.S. Import and Export Bank will invest 90
million Dollars in oil tapping in Cabinda.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, she added, the bank is undertaking negotiations
with Angola National Petroleum Corporation and Chevron Oil
Company in the United States on the provision of 350 million
Dollars to purchase petro equipment from the United States.
</P>
<P>
According to her, revenues from petroleum is of vital
importance to Angola's rehabilitation, the disbanding of
remaining militiamen and the consolidation of national
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Angola is the fifth leg of Albright's African tour. During her
short stay in Angola, she also met with Angolan President Eduardo
dos Santos on peace process in the country and bilateral issues.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of state also held talks with Blondin Beye,
U.N. representative in Angola and UNITA leaders in Luanda on
issues concerning the peace process.
</P>
<P>
This is Albright's first visit to Angola in here present
capacity. Her next stop is South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
